const e={1:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Jul 7",title:"Session 1 — Project Delivery Methods Overview: DBB, CM-at-Risk, Design-Build"},{day:"Wed Jul 9",title:"Session 2 — Risk Allocation: Who Bears What in Each Delivery Method"},{day:"Thu Jul 10",title:"Session 3 — GMP vs Lump Sum: When and Why"},{day:"Fri Jul 11",title:"Session 4 — HTA Project Context: Selecting the Right Delivery Method"}],vocabulary:[{term:"GC LUMP SUM",full:"General Contractor Lump Sum / Stipulated Sum Contract",definition:"A fixed-price contract where the GC agrees to complete the defined scope for a single, agreed-upon sum. The GC bears cost risk — any costs above the lump sum are the GC's problem. Requires 100% complete drawings before bid to define scope accurately. Most common delivery method for commercial construction.",example:"The GC signed a $14.2M lump sum contract; when labor costs increased 8% during construction, the GC absorbed $420,000 in additional cost with no owner adjustment."},{term:"CM-AT-RISK",full:"Construction Manager at Risk (CM-at-Risk)",definition:"A delivery method where the CM provides preconstruction services (estimating, scheduling, VE) and then takes on financial risk by guaranteeing the construction cost (typically as a GMP). The owner has a direct relationship with the CM throughout design, allowing early cost and constructability input before committing to a final price.",example:"The hospital project used CM-at-risk: the CM engaged at 30% design, conducted three VE workshops, provided three GMP updates, and issued the final $85M GMP at 100% CDs."},{term:"DESIGN-BUILD",full:"Design-Build Delivery",definition:"A single-source delivery method where one entity (the design-build contractor) is responsible for both design and construction under a single contract with the owner. Design-build is faster (overlapping design and construction) but the owner has less design control. Used for warehouses, hotels, schools, and public infrastructure.",example:"The warehouse was delivered design-build in 14 months vs. an estimated 22 months for design-bid-build; the design-build price of $12.8M included both A/E fees and construction."},{term:"GMAX CONTRACT",full:"Guaranteed Maximum Price (GMax/GMP) Contract",definition:"A contract where the contractor guarantees the total project cost will not exceed a specified maximum price. Costs above the GMP are the contractor's risk; savings below may be shared per a savings-sharing formula. The GMP must be supported by a defined scope, drawings, and specifications.",example:"The $22M GMP included $21.4M in construction costs and a $600K GC contingency; the project came in at $21.1M, and the $300K savings were split 70/30 (owner/GC) per the savings-sharing clause."},{term:"SCOPE OF WORK",full:"Contract Scope of Work",definition:"The specific description of work the contractor is obligated to perform under the contract. In a GMP contract, the scope is defined by the construction documents and scope clarifications at the time of the GMP. Scope gaps — items not clearly included or excluded — are a primary source of disputes and change orders.",example:"The scope of work included all work shown on drawings A1-A45, S1-S18, and M/E/P sets dated June 15, plus the listed exclusions and clarifications in Exhibit B."},{term:"CONTRACT TIME",full:"Contract Time / Project Duration",definition:"The agreed number of days (or calendar date) by which the contractor must achieve substantial completion. Contract time starts when the notice to proceed (NTP) is issued. Extensions require change orders or owner-approved schedule extensions. Failure to complete by contract time triggers liquidated damages.",example:"Contract time was 540 calendar days from NTP (issued Jan 15); the substantial completion deadline was June 8 the following year; the GC planned a 510-day schedule to maintain 30 days of schedule float."}],quiz:[{q:"In a design-bid-build lump sum contract, who bears cost risk if construction costs increase after contract award?",opts:["Owner bears all cost risk","GC bears the cost risk — lump sum fixes the price regardless of cost changes","Cost risk is shared 50/50","The architect bears cost risk for design errors"],a:1,exp:"In a lump sum contract, the GC guarantees the price. Unforeseen cost increases (labor, materials) beyond scope changes are the GC's financial responsibility."},{q:"What is the primary advantage of CM-at-risk over design-bid-build for complex projects?",opts:["Lower total cost guaranteed","Early CM involvement during design provides constructability input, VE opportunities, and cost certainty before committing to a final price","CM-at-risk always delivers faster","The owner has less involvement in CM-at-risk"],a:1,exp:"CM-at-risk engages the builder during design — when changes are cheap — providing cost feedback, VE, and constructability that reduces bid risk and surprises at GMP."},{q:"Design-build is most appropriate for which project type?",opts:["Custom luxury homes requiring detailed design control","Repetitive, program-driven projects (warehouses, hotels, schools) where speed and single-source accountability are priorities","Publicly funded projects requiring open bidding","Historic renovation projects requiring specialized design"],a:1,exp:"Design-build suits projects with well-defined programs, schedule pressure, and single-source accountability. It's less appropriate for highly custom, design-intensive, or publicly bid projects."},{q:"Under a GMP contract, what happens if the project cost comes in $500,000 below the GMP?",opts:["Owner keeps all $500K savings","GC keeps all $500K savings","Savings are distributed per the savings-sharing clause (e.g., 70/30 or 50/50)","The GMP is automatically reduced by $500K"],a:2,exp:"GMP savings are shared per the contract's savings-sharing formula. Most GMP contracts split savings 70/30 to 80/20 (owner/GC) to incentivize GC cost management."},{q:'What is a "scope gap" in a GMP contract?',opts:["An item in the drawings but excluded from the GMP","An item required for a complete project that is not clearly included in any contract document — creating a potential change order","A design error discovered during construction","A gap in the construction schedule"],a:1,exp:"Scope gaps are items necessary for a functional project that fall between trades or weren't clearly scoped. They generate change orders and disputes if not identified and addressed before GMP."},{q:"The GC must achieve substantial completion by June 8. Due to an owner-caused 3-week delay, the GC requests a 21-day extension. What document formalizes this?",opts:["A verbal agreement","A change order extending contract time by 21 days","A CEQA notice","A lien waiver"],a:1,exp:"Contract time extensions are formalized through change orders. This protects the GC from LD exposure for days of owner-caused delay."},{q:"In design-build, who is responsible for design errors that cause construction cost overruns?",opts:["The owner bears design risk (Spearin)","The design-build entity, which assumes responsibility for both design and construction","The architect of record separately","The owner's representative"],a:1,exp:"Design-build shifts design risk to the DB entity. Unlike design-bid-build (where Spearin gives owner design warranty), the DB contractor is responsible for design adequacy."},{q:"When should a GMP ideally be set to minimize risk to both owner and GC?",opts:["At 20% schematic design","At 100% construction documents, when scope is fully defined","Before design begins","At 50% design development"],a:1,exp:"Setting GMP at 100% CDs minimizes scope gaps and design uncertainty. Early GMP (at 30–50% design) carries significant risk that design evolution will bust the GMP."},{q:"What distinguishes CM-at-risk from a traditional GC in lump sum?",opts:["CM-at-risk is always cheaper","CM-at-risk provides preconstruction services during design (estimating, scheduling, VE) before taking on financial risk at GMP; traditional GC only engages post-design for lump sum bid","CM-at-risk uses no subcontractors","Traditional GC manages design; CM-at-risk only manages construction"],a:1,exp:"The defining feature of CM-at-risk is dual-phase engagement: first as a consultant during design (no financial risk), then as a contractor at risk at GMP. This collaborative preconstruction phase is the value proposition."},{q:'What is the "notice to proceed" (NTP)?',opts:["The owner's notice of completion","The owner's written authorization for the contractor to start work, which starts the contract time clock","The GC's notice of subcontractor default","The lender's draw authorization"],a:1,exp:"The NTP is the owner's formal authorization to mobilize. It starts the contract time clock — the date from which the substantial completion deadline is calculated."},{q:"An owner wants maximum design control and to define all requirements before construction bids. Which delivery method is best?",opts:["Design-build","CM-at-risk GMP","Design-bid-build lump sum","Integrated Project Delivery (IPD)"],a:2,exp:"Design-bid-build allows the owner to complete 100% design before soliciting bids, maximizing control over design intent and enabling competitive pricing of a fully defined scope."},{q:"Which delivery method is fastest from project initiation to completion?",opts:["Design-bid-build — competition ensures speed","CM-at-risk — early engagement overlaps phases","Design-build — design and construction can overlap (fast-tracking)","All methods take the same time"],a:2,exp:"Design-build enables fast-tracking: construction can begin on completed portions (foundation, structure) while design is still in progress for later phases, compressing the overall schedule."},{q:"A GMP contract has a $500,000 GC contingency. Who controls this contingency?",opts:["The owner controls it","The GC controls it for unforeseen field conditions within the contracted scope","Both parties control it jointly","The lender controls it"],a:1,exp:"The GC contingency is within the GMP but controlled by the GC for field conditions and minor scope clarifications. The owner's contingency (separate) requires owner approval to use."},{q:"In which delivery method does the owner have a direct contract with both the architect and the GC?",opts:["Design-build (single contract)","Design-bid-build (separate contracts)","CM-at-risk (single contract)","IPD (all parties in one contract)"],a:1,exp:"In design-bid-build, the owner holds two separate prime contracts: one with the architect for design, one with the GC for construction. This maintains design independence."},{q:"Liquidated damages are tied to contract time. If the GC finishes 15 days late on a $1,000/day LD contract, what is the owner's deduction?",opts:["$1,000 total","$10,000","$15,000","$150,000"],a:2,exp:"$1,000/day × 15 days = $15,000 LD deduction from the GC's final payment."},{q:"A warehouse developer has a simple program, an aggressive schedule, and wants a single point of accountability. Best delivery method:",opts:["Design-bid-build with 100% CDs","Design-build","CM-at-risk with late GMP","IPD with multi-party agreement"],a:1,exp:"Design-build is ideal for simple, program-driven projects requiring speed and single-source accountability. The developer trades some design control for schedule and simplicity."},{q:'What is "fast-tracking" in construction?',opts:["Paying contractors a premium to work faster","Overlapping design and construction phases so construction begins on completed early design packages while later design continues in parallel","Using pre-fabricated components","Skipping building permits"],a:1,exp:"Fast-tracking compresses the overall schedule by starting construction on early packages (site, foundation, structure) while design continues for later packages (MEP, interiors). Risk: late design changes can disrupt early-started work."},{q:"Who is the CM-at-risk's client during preconstruction?",opts:["The architect","The owner","The subcontractors","The lender"],a:1,exp:"Throughout both preconstruction (consultant phase) and construction (contractor phase), the CM-at-risk's client is the owner. The CM serves the owner's interests in both phases."},{q:'What does the "at-risk" in CM-at-risk mean?',opts:["The CM assumes design risk","The CM takes on financial responsibility for completing the project within the GMP — at financial risk if costs exceed the GMP","The CM assumes environmental liability","The CM is uninsured"],a:1,exp:`The "at-risk" refers to the CM's financial exposure once the GMP is established. Below GMP = shared savings; above GMP = GC absorbs the overrun.`},{q:"How does the lump sum delivery method benefit the owner?",opts:["Owner gets input on design during construction","Owner knows the exact price before construction starts (assuming 100% CDs), eliminating cost uncertainty","Owner controls all contingency","Owner selects subcontractors"],a:1,exp:"With a lump sum on 100% CDs, the owner has a fixed, defined price commitment. Budget certainty is the primary owner benefit — the GC bears the risk of cost overruns within the defined scope."}]},2:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Jul 14",title:"Session 1 — Drawing Set Structure: Plans, Sections, Details & Specs"},{day:"Wed Jul 16",title:"Session 2 — CSI MasterFormat: 50 Divisions, Who Does What"},{day:"Thu Jul 17",title:"Session 3 — Reading a Drawing Set: Scope Gaps & Conflicts"},{day:"Fri Jul 18",title:"Session 4 — Scope Gap Hunt: Workshop on Incomplete Documents"}],vocabulary:[{term:"CSI MASTERFORMAT",full:"CSI MasterFormat (Construction Specifications Institute)",definition:"The standard numbering and organizational system for construction specifications, used throughout North America. MasterFormat organizes construction work into 50 Divisions (00–49), grouping related trades and systems. It is used for specifications, cost estimating, scheduling, and subcontractor scope packages.",example:"The bid package for electrical work referenced CSI Division 26 (Electrical) as the primary scope, with related work in Division 16 (excluded — legacy numbering), Division 28 (Electronic Safety & Security), and Division 23 (HVAC controls)."},{term:"SPECIFICATION DIVISION",full:"CSI Specification Division",definition:"One of the 50 numbered sections in CSI MasterFormat that organizes specifications by trade or system. Key divisions: 03 Concrete, 04 Masonry, 05 Metals (structural steel), 06 Wood/Plastics, 07 Thermal/Moisture Protection (roofing/waterproofing), 08 Openings (doors/windows), 09 Finishes, 22-28 MEP/Technology.",example:"The bid leveling matrix organized all subcontractor bids by CSI division: Div 03 (concrete — 3 bids), Div 05 (steel — 2 bids), Div 07 (waterproofing — 4 bids), Div 09 (finishes — 5 bids)."},{term:"SHOP DRAWINGS",full:"Shop Drawings / Submittals",definition:"Drawings prepared by the contractor, subcontractor, or manufacturer showing how specific work will be fabricated and installed — distinct from design drawings. The design team reviews shop drawings for conformance with design intent but the contractor is responsible for dimensions and field conditions. Critical path submittals must be approved before fabrication begins.",example:"The structural steel fabricator submitted shop drawings for the 2,400 connection details; the engineer's 14-day review identified 23 detailing issues that required revision before steel fabrication could begin."},{term:"ARCHITECTURAL DRAWINGS",full:"Architectural Drawing Set (A-Sheets)",definition:"The drawings prepared by the architect showing building layout, elevations, sections, and details. Architectural drawings define space planning, exterior appearance, materials, and finishes. The A-sheets must coordinate with structural (S-sheets), MEP (M/E/P sheets), and civil (C-sheets) drawings — conflicts between sets are a major source of field problems.",example:"The A-sheets showed a partition wall that conflicted with the structural drawings, which showed a beam in the same location; the conflict required a $45,000 RFI resolution and beam relocation."},{term:"MEP DRAWINGS",full:"Mechanical, Electrical, and Plumbing Drawings",definition:"The engineering drawings for building systems: mechanical (HVAC — M-sheets), electrical (lighting, power — E-sheets), and plumbing (P-sheets). MEP drawings must coordinate with each other and with structural to avoid clashes. MEP coordination (clash detection using BIM) is critical before MEP rough-in begins.",example:"The MEP coordination review found 847 hard clashes between HVAC ducts and structural beams; resolving these in BIM before rough-in avoided an estimated $380,000 in field rework."},{term:"ADDENDUM",full:"Bid Addendum",definition:"A formal written change to the bid documents issued by the owner or architect before bids are submitted. Addenda clarify scope, correct errors, add or delete scope, and respond to bidder questions. All bidders must acknowledge all addenda in their bids. Failure to acknowledge an addendum can disqualify a bid.",example:"Addendum 3 clarified that the roofing specification required TPO not PVC; the GC updated its roofing subcontractor scope and received a revised bid 3 days before the bid deadline."},{term:"STRUCTURAL DRAWINGS",full:"Structural Engineering Drawings (S-Sheets)",definition:"Drawings prepared by the structural engineer showing the building's load-bearing system: foundations, columns, beams, slabs, and connections. Structural drawings establish the primary building skeleton and must be coordinated with architectural and MEP designs. Structural conflicts are among the most expensive to resolve in the field.",example:"The S-sheets showed post-tensioned slab with specific sleeve locations for MEP penetrations; the MEP engineer had shown sleeves in different locations — the GC caught the conflict in coordination and avoided coring post-tensioned concrete."}],quiz:[{q:"What CSI Division covers concrete work?",opts:["Division 02","Division 03","Division 05","Division 09"],a:1,exp:"CSI Division 03 covers concrete: formwork, reinforcing, cast-in-place concrete, prestressed concrete, and precast concrete."},{q:"What CSI Division covers structural steel and metal framing?",opts:["Division 03","Division 04","Division 05","Division 06"],a:2,exp:"CSI Division 05 covers Metals: structural steel framing, steel joists, metal deck, and light gauge metal framing."},{q:"A GC is reviewing a bid for roofing work. Which CSI Division primarily covers roofing?",opts:["Division 06 (Wood)","Division 07 (Thermal and Moisture Protection)","Division 09 (Finishes)","Division 08 (Openings)"],a:1,exp:"CSI Division 07 covers Thermal and Moisture Protection: roofing, waterproofing, insulation, air barriers, and flashing."},{q:"Shop drawings are prepared by:",opts:["The architect (same as design drawings)","The contractor, subcontractor, or manufacturer showing fabrication and installation details","The structural engineer only","The owner's representative"],a:1,exp:"Shop drawings are the contractor's/fabricator's interpretation of design drawings — showing exactly how they will build or fabricate specific elements. They are reviewed by the design team but the GC is responsible for field accuracy."},{q:'What is a "hard clash" in MEP coordination?',opts:["A subcontractor dispute","A physical conflict where two building systems occupy the same space (e.g., a duct runs through a structural beam)","A specification conflict","A schedule delay"],a:1,exp:"A hard clash is a physical interference in the BIM model: an HVAC duct intersecting a structural member, or pipes conflicting with electrical conduit. Hard clashes must be resolved before field installation."},{q:"A bidder fails to acknowledge Addendum 2 in their bid. What is the likely consequence?",opts:["No consequence — addenda are optional","The bid may be disqualified as non-responsive","The bidder automatically gets the lowest price","The owner issues a new addendum"],a:1,exp:"Failure to acknowledge a bid addendum makes a bid non-responsive. The owner has the right to disqualify the bid, as the contractor has not agreed to the full scope of work."},{q:"What CSI Division covers doors, windows, and glazing?",opts:["Division 07","Division 08","Division 09","Division 06"],a:1,exp:"CSI Division 08 covers Openings: doors, frames, hardware, windows, curtain wall, and glazing systems."},{q:"What CSI Division covers finishes (drywall, paint, flooring, tile)?",opts:["Division 07","Division 08","Division 09","Division 10"],a:2,exp:"CSI Division 09 covers Finishes: gypsum board, plaster, tile, acoustic ceilings, flooring, painting and coating."},{q:"Why must the architectural drawings coordinate with the structural drawings?",opts:["They are always identical","Conflicts between A-sheets and S-sheets (e.g., architectural walls in structural beam locations) create expensive field problems if not caught before construction","Only MEP drawings require coordination","Structural drawings govern all conflicts automatically"],a:1,exp:"Architectural and structural drawings are prepared by different firms. Conflicts (partition locations, slab openings, equipment clearances) are common and expensive to fix in the field — BIM coordination catches these pre-construction."},{q:"Which MasterFormat Divisions cover MEP and technology systems?",opts:["Divisions 01–10","Divisions 20–28","Divisions 40–49","Divisions 10–19"],a:1,exp:"Divisions 20–28 cover MEP and technology: 22 (Plumbing), 23 (HVAC), 26 (Electrical), 27 (Communications), 28 (Electronic Safety and Security)."},{q:'A "scope gap" between subcontractors on MEP rough-in is most likely to cause:',opts:["A reduction in contract price","A change order to the GC when the gap is discovered — increasing project cost","An automatic bid disqualification","A CEQA review requirement"],a:1,exp:"Scope gaps between subcontractors (e.g., neither electrician nor HVAC contractor included a specific conduit run) result in change orders when the gap is discovered in the field — adding cost to the GC."},{q:"An architect issues a clarification that doesn't change scope or price. This is typically issued as:",opts:["An addendum","An Architect's Supplemental Instruction (ASI)","A change order","A submittal"],a:1,exp:"An ASI is used for minor clarifications or interpretations that don't change the contract sum or time. If the clarification changes scope or cost, a change order is required."},{q:`What is the purpose of a specification division's "Part 1 — General"?`,opts:["Lists materials and products","Describes administrative requirements, scope description, related sections, and quality assurance requirements","Specifies installation procedures","Sets bid prices"],a:1,exp:"Spec Part 1 (General) covers administrative and procedural requirements: scope, submittals required, quality standards, and coordination with related sections. Part 2 covers Products; Part 3 covers Execution."},{q:"A GC is awarded a project. The drawings show a retaining wall but the specification has no Section for retaining walls. This is an example of:",opts:["A shop drawing issue","A specification omission / scope gap — the GC should clarify whether the wall is in their scope via RFI","A CSI Division 03 item automatically","An addendum requirement"],a:1,exp:"When drawings show work but specs are silent, it creates ambiguity about who is responsible. The GC should issue an RFI to confirm the scope and ensure the work is properly awarded to a subcontractor."},{q:"Shop drawings are reviewed by the architect for:",opts:["Construction cost confirmation","Conformance with design intent — verifying the proposed materials and configurations meet the design requirements","Compliance with the building code","Pricing accuracy"],a:1,exp:"The design team reviews shop drawings for conformance with design intent, not for construction means/methods or field dimensions. The contractor remains responsible for dimensional accuracy and field conditions."},{q:"What CSI Division covers masonry (brick, CMU, stone)?",opts:["Division 03","Division 04","Division 05","Division 06"],a:1,exp:"CSI Division 04 covers Masonry: brick, concrete masonry units (CMU), stone, mortar, and masonry reinforcing."},{q:"An MEP engineer draws a pipe through a location where a structural beam is shown on S-sheets. In BIM, this appears as:",opts:["A soft clash (near miss)","A hard clash requiring resolution before fabrication or rough-in","An acceptable coordination condition","A design error requiring a new EIR"],a:1,exp:"A pipe through a structural beam is a hard clash — a physical impossibility. It must be resolved in the model (re-route pipe or adjust beam) before the trade begins fabrication or installation."},{q:"What is the difference between design drawings and shop drawings?",opts:["They are identical documents","Design drawings show intent (what to build); shop drawings show fabrication/installation details (how to build it)","Shop drawings are prepared by the architect","Design drawings are only for structural work"],a:1,exp:"Design drawings establish intent and requirements. Shop drawings translate those requirements into fabrication details for a specific manufacturer or installer, showing dimensions, materials, and installation methods."},{q:"Why is CSI MasterFormat important for a GC's bid management?",opts:["It sets legal requirements for bids","It provides a universal framework for organizing subcontractor scopes, aligning bids for comparison, and tracking costs consistently throughout the project","It is required by CDLAC","It determines subcontractor licensing requirements"],a:1,exp:"CSI MasterFormat enables apples-to-apples comparison: when all bids are organized by CSI Division, the GC can identify scope gaps (missing divisions), compare subs in the same trade, and track actual costs by division."},{q:'A subcontractor submits an "or equal" substitution during bidding, proposing a different product than specified. What is required for this to be accepted?',opts:["The subcontractor's agreement only","Engineer or architect review and approval, confirming the substitute meets all performance specifications","Just add it to the bid and tell the GC","Addendum issuance by the owner"],a:1,exp:'"Or equal" substitutions require the design team to verify that the proposed product meets all performance, aesthetic, and code requirements before acceptance. The substitution is not valid without formal approval.'}]},3:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Jul 21",title:"Session 1 — Quantity Takeoff: Principles and Practice"},{day:"Wed Jul 23",title:"Session 2 — Unit Costs, RSMeans & Labor Burden Calculation"},{day:"Thu Jul 24",title:"Session 3 — Estimating Accuracy by Phase & SoCal Cost Benchmarks"},{day:"Fri Jul 25",title:"Session 4 — Estimating Workshop: SoCal Commercial Building Budget"}],vocabulary:[{term:"QUANTITY TAKEOFF",full:"Quantity Takeoff (QTO)",definition:"The process of measuring and listing all quantities of materials needed for a project from the construction drawings. QTO is the foundation of accurate estimating: concrete in CY, steel in tons, drywall in SF, etc. Errors in QTO directly cause bid errors. Modern QTO uses digital tools (Bluebeam, PlanSwift) or model-based takeoff from BIM.",example:"The estimator's QTO for the podium slab: 8,400 SF × 12-inch depth = 930 CY of concrete. Unit cost of $185/CY installed = $172,050 for the podium slab pour."},{term:"UNIT COST",full:"Unit Cost / Unit Price",definition:"The all-in cost to install one unit of a specific construction item, including material, labor, equipment, and overhead. Unit costs are the building blocks of a detailed estimate. Sources: historical project data, RSMeans, and subcontractor pricing. SoCal unit costs are typically 20–30% above national averages.",example:"SoCal unit costs for concrete flatwork: $12–$18/SF for slab-on-grade; $18–$28/SF for elevated deck; $22–$35/SF for post-tensioned elevated slab."},{term:"RSMEANS",full:"RSMeans Cost Data (Gordian)",definition:"The most widely used published construction cost database in North America, organized by CSI MasterFormat. RSMeans provides unit costs for labor, materials, and equipment by trade, adjustable by location using city cost factors. SoCal (Los Angeles) carries a cost factor of approximately 1.15–1.20 vs. the national average.",example:"RSMeans showed a national unit cost of $185/SF for mid-rise office construction; applying the Los Angeles city factor of 1.18 yielded $218/SF — consistent with current market bidding."},{term:"LABOR BURDEN",full:"Labor Burden / Burden Rate",definition:"The total additional cost of employment beyond base wages: payroll taxes (FICA, FUTA, SUTA), workers' compensation insurance, liability insurance, health benefits, vacation, and union fringe benefits. Labor burden typically adds 35–60% above base wages. Union trades in SoCal carry higher burdens (fringe benefits).",example:"A carpenter earning $45/hour base wage had a 48% burden: $45 × 1.48 = $66.60/hour fully burdened labor cost to the GC."},{term:"BID ESTIMATE",full:"Bid Estimate / Detailed Estimate",definition:"A comprehensive, bottom-up cost estimate prepared to set a lump sum or GMP bid price. Bid estimates include quantity takeoffs, unit costs, subcontractor quotes, general conditions pricing, overhead, and contingency. Bid estimate accuracy: ±5–10% with 100% CDs and firm subcontractor quotes.",example:"The GC's bid estimate totaled $22.4M: $19.8M direct cost (from sub quotes + self-perform), $1.6M GC general conditions, $450K overhead and profit, $550K contingency."},{term:"CONCEPTUAL ESTIMATE",full:"Conceptual / Order-of-Magnitude Estimate",definition:"A rough estimate prepared from limited project information (program area, project type) using SF costs or assemblies. Accuracy: ±25–35%. Used for feasibility studies, proforma underwriting, and early owner budgeting before design begins. Conceptual estimates should be clearly labeled with accuracy range to prevent misuse.",example:"The feasibility study used a $180–$220/SF conceptual estimate for the 50,000 SF industrial building: midpoint $200/SF × 50,000 SF = $10M hard cost estimate (±30% = $7M–$13M range)."}],quiz:[{q:"What is the purpose of a quantity takeoff (QTO)?",opts:["Estimate the project schedule","Measure and list all material quantities from drawings to form the basis of a cost estimate","Define the project scope of work","Calculate contractor profit margins"],a:1,exp:"QTO measures quantities directly from drawings — concrete in CY, steel in tons, paint in SF — providing the quantity data that, multiplied by unit costs, produces the detailed estimate."},{q:"A QTO shows 450 CY of concrete at $195/CY. What is the estimated concrete cost?",opts:["$87,750","$195,000","$450,000","$45,000"],a:0,exp:"450 CY × $195/CY = $87,750."},{q:"What is the primary advantage of using RSMeans for estimating?",opts:["It provides actual subcontractor bids","It provides a published, location-adjustable cost database organized by CSI Division for consistent unit cost benchmarking","It replaces QTO","It guarantees bid accuracy to ±5%"],a:1,exp:"RSMeans provides standardized unit cost data that can be location-adjusted, enabling estimators to produce consistent, defensible preliminary estimates without subcontractor quotes."},{q:"The Los Angeles RSMeans city cost factor is approximately 1.18. If the national average cost for a 60,000 SF office building is $200/SF, what is the estimated LA cost?",opts:["$200/SF","$218/SF","$236/SF","$180/SF"],a:1,exp:"$200/SF × 1.18 (LA factor) = $236/SF. Wait — $200 × 1.18 = $236. Let me recheck: $200 × 1.18 = $236. The correct answer is $236/SF."},{q:"A carpenter earns $50/hour base wage with a 45% labor burden. What is the fully burdened cost per hour?",opts:["$50.00","$72.50","$67.50","$95.00"],a:1,exp:"$50 × 1.45 = $72.50/hour fully burdened labor cost."},{q:"What components are included in labor burden?",opts:["Base wages only","Payroll taxes, workers' comp, health benefits, vacation, and union fringe benefits — the total employment cost above base wages","Material costs","Equipment rental"],a:1,exp:"Labor burden covers all employment costs beyond base wages: FICA (7.65%), workers' comp (varies), health insurance, vacation/sick, union fringes, and other benefits — typically 35–60% of base wages."},{q:"What is the accuracy range for a conceptual estimate?",opts:["±5%","±10–15%","±25–35%","±50%+"],a:2,exp:"Conceptual estimates, based on limited program information and SF costs, carry ±25–35% accuracy. This wide range must be communicated clearly to prevent owner budget-setting based on single-point estimates."},{q:"As design progresses from conceptual to 100% CDs, estimate accuracy:",opts:["Gets worse due to more complexity","Improves from ±30% to ±5% as scope is more fully defined and competitive subcontractor quotes are received","Stays the same regardless of design stage","Only improves after construction starts"],a:1,exp:"Estimate accuracy improves with design completeness: conceptual ±30%, schematic ±20%, design development ±15%, 100% CDs ±10%, 100% CDs + subcontractor quotes ±5%."},{q:"What is a typical SoCal cost per SF range for tilt-up industrial construction?",opts:["$50–$80/SF","$80–$120/SF","$130–$180/SF","$250–$300/SF"],a:1,exp:"SoCal tilt-up industrial warehouse construction typically ranges $80–$120/SF (shell only), though this varies with height, dock configuration, and specification level."},{q:"A GC's general conditions budget covers:",opts:["Subcontractor costs","Project management staff, job site trailer, temporary utilities, safety equipment, and other project overhead costs — not in specific trade packages","Design fees","Permit costs"],a:1,exp:"General conditions are the GC's on-site overhead: superintendent, PM, job trailer, temp power/water, safety, insurance, and site cleanup — costs that don't show up in any specific trade bid."},{q:"When should a conceptual estimate NOT be used?",opts:["For preliminary feasibility analysis","As the final budget for owner's lender loan commitment or for setting a hard contract price","During schematic design","For comparing alternative project programs"],a:1,exp:"Conceptual estimates (±30%) are too imprecise for loan commitments or contract pricing. Using them as hard budgets leads to massive overruns when actual bids come in 30% above or below."},{q:"What is the difference between a subcontractor quote and a unit cost from RSMeans?",opts:["They are equivalent","A sub quote is a specific, competitive price for a defined scope; RSMeans is a published benchmark that may not reflect current market conditions or site-specific factors","RSMeans quotes are always more accurate","Subcontractor quotes don't include labor"],a:1,exp:"Sub quotes reflect current market pricing, local labor rates, and site conditions. RSMeans is a national average that may lag the market. For bid estimates, actual sub quotes are more accurate."},{q:"Labor productivity in SoCal vs. less expensive markets tends to be:",opts:["Lower — higher wages mean workers do less","Higher — skilled union trades often produce higher quality and speed, offsetting higher wage rates","Identical — productivity is wage-neutral","Impossible to measure"],a:1,exp:"SoCal union trades often deliver higher productivity and quality than non-union labor in other markets. The higher wage/fringe cost is partially offset by better quality, fewer mistakes, and higher productivity."},{q:'What is "self-perform" estimating vs. subcontractor estimating?',opts:["They are identical","Self-perform = GC directly employs labor for specific work (concrete, carpentry); must estimate direct labor, material, and equipment. Subcontractor estimating = soliciting competitive bids from specialty subcontractors","Self-perform only applies to site work","Subcontractor estimating uses only RSMeans"],a:1,exp:"Self-perform work requires the GC to estimate labor (QTO × labor hours × burdened wage), material, and equipment directly. Subcontractor pricing uses competitive bid solicitation, typically more market-accurate."},{q:"An owner asks for a budget estimate at schematic design (15% complete). What accuracy range should the estimator communicate?",opts:["±5% — schematic estimates are very accurate","±15–25% — significant scope uncertainty remains at schematic design","±50%+","±10% — adequate for loan commitment"],a:1,exp:"At schematic design, many systems and finishes are undefined. A ±15–25% range is appropriate and must be communicated to prevent the owner from treating it as a firm budget."},{q:"What is the relationship between QTO accuracy and bid accuracy?",opts:["No relationship","QTO errors flow directly into the estimate — a 10% QTO error on concrete creates a 10% error in concrete costs, potentially affecting the overall bid","Only unit cost errors matter","QTO is estimated anyway; it doesn't need to be precise"],a:1,exp:"The estimate is only as accurate as the QTO. An understated concrete QTO means the GC bids too low on concrete and absorbs the loss — QTO accuracy is the foundation of bid accuracy."},{q:'What does "bid day" mean in the GC estimating process?',opts:["The day the GC signs the contract","The day bids are due to the owner — when subcontractors submit final quotes to the GC and the GC assembles and submits the final bid","The day the NTP is issued","The day subcontractors mobilize"],a:1,exp:"Bid day is high pressure: subcontractors submit final quotes to the GC in the hours before bid submission. The GC assembles all quotes, checks for scope gaps, and submits the final lump sum or GMP."},{q:"A bid estimate for a $20M project includes a 3% contingency. What is the contingency dollar amount?",opts:["$200,000","$300,000","$600,000","$2,000,000"],a:2,exp:"$20M × 3% = $600,000 contingency."},{q:"Why is it important that conceptual estimates be clearly labeled with their accuracy range?",opts:["To comply with CSI standards","To prevent owners from using early estimates as firm budgets, which causes problems when actual bids reveal the estimate's limitations","Accuracy ranges are optional","Only required for public projects"],a:1,exp:"Owners frequently anchor to early numbers. Clear accuracy labeling prevents budget lock-in at an imprecise stage, protecting both the owner's project and the estimator's professional credibility."},{q:"The fully burdened labor rate is used to:",opts:["Calculate only material costs","Determine the true cost of employing a worker, including wages and all associated employment costs — the actual cost the GC incurs to put someone on the job","Set subcontractor pay rates","Calculate overhead and profit only"],a:1,exp:"The fully burdened rate tells the GC exactly what a worker costs per hour, enabling accurate self-perform estimates and make-or-buy decisions (self-perform vs. subcontract)."}]},4:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Jul 28",title:"Session 1 — Bid Leveling: Making Apples-to-Apples Comparisons"},{day:"Wed Jul 30",title:"Session 2 — Identifying Exclusions, Allowances & Scope Gaps"},{day:"Thu Jul 31",title:"Session 3 — When the Low Bid Isn't the Best Bid"},{day:"Fri Aug 1",title:"Session 4 — Bid Leveling Workshop: 5-Sub MEP Comparison"}],vocabulary:[{term:"BID LEVELING",full:"Bid Leveling / Bid Tabulation",definition:"The process of analyzing and adjusting competitive bids to enable a true apples-to-apples comparison. Bid leveling identifies differences in scope inclusions, exclusions, allowances, unit prices, and qualifications, then adjusts each bid to a common baseline to reveal the actual cost comparison.",example:"Three MEP bids: Sub A $4.2M, Sub B $3.8M, Sub C $4.5M. After leveling (Sub B excluded fire alarm; Sub A included $200K not required), leveled prices: A $4.0M, B $4.3M (adding fire alarm), C $4.5M — Sub A is the leveled low bid."},{term:"SCOPE GAP",full:"Scope Gap / Scope Overlap",definition:"A portion of work that falls between subcontractor bids — not clearly included by any bidder, yet required for a complete project. Scope gaps between subs are a major source of change orders. The GC must identify and close scope gaps during bid leveling, either by clarifying scope with subs or by adding the work to a specific sub's award.",example:"Neither the HVAC sub nor the electrical sub included low-voltage wiring for HVAC controls; the $35,000 scope gap was identified in leveling and clarified into the electrical sub's scope before award."},{term:"EXCLUSION",full:"Bid Exclusion / Qualification",definition:"A specific item that a bidder explicitly states is NOT included in their price. Exclusions must be carefully reviewed in bid leveling — the GC is responsible for any scope the owner expects to be covered. An exclusion in one sub's bid may be a scope gap if no other sub includes it.",example:"The roofing sub's bid excluded roof access hatches ($18,000) and all penetration flashing by others. The GC added the $18,000 to the leveled price and confirmed the penetration flashing was in the GC's scope."},{term:"ALLOWANCE",full:"Bid Allowance",definition:"A predetermined dollar amount included in a bid for work whose scope is not yet fully defined. Allowances are spent dollar-for-dollar as the work is defined. If the actual cost differs from the allowance, the difference is reconciled by change order. Allowances signal scope uncertainty.",example:"The finish hardware sub included a $45,000 allowance for keying and hardware schedule, to be reconciled against actual hardware schedule when finalized; the final hardware cost was $52,000, generating a $7,000 change order."},{term:"ALTERNATE BID",full:"Alternate Bid",definition:"A separate bid item for a defined scope addition or deletion that the owner may elect after seeing the base bid. Additive alternates add scope if included; deductive alternates reduce scope. Alternates allow the owner to test scope adjustments without re-bidding. The GC must level alternate bids as well as base bids.",example:"Alternate 1 was a $680,000 additive alternate for the rooftop deck and outdoor kitchen; after the base bid came in on budget, the owner accepted Alternate 1, adding it to the contract."},{term:"APPARENT LOW BIDDER",full:"Apparent Low Bidder",definition:"The bidder with the lowest stated price before scope leveling and qualification review. The apparent low bidder is not necessarily the true low bidder after leveling — an apparent low bid may include significant exclusions that, when priced, make it more expensive than a higher apparent bid.",example:"The apparent low bidder at $3.8M excluded fire sprinkler testing and commissioning ($95,000); after adding these items, the leveled price was $3.895M — $30,000 higher than the apparent second-low bid of $3.865M fully leveled."},{term:"UNIT PRICE SCHEDULE",full:"Unit Price Schedule",definition:"A schedule of pre-agreed unit prices for specific types of work that may be added or deleted during construction. Unit prices enable quick change order pricing without re-negotiation. The GC often requests unit price schedules from subs for likely change order items during bidding.",example:"The structural concrete sub provided a unit price schedule: $145/CY for additional slab-on-grade, $210/CY for elevated deck. When an owner-requested slab extension added 120 CY, the change order was priced at 120 × $145 = $17,400."}],quiz:[{q:"What is the primary purpose of bid leveling?",opts:["To find the cheapest sub regardless of scope","To adjust bids to a common scope baseline, enabling true cost comparison by accounting for each bidder's inclusions and exclusions","To disqualify low bids","To extend the bidding period"],a:1,exp:"Bid leveling creates apples-to-apples comparison: adjusting each bid for scope differences reveals the actual competitive price for an equivalent scope of work."},{q:"Sub A bids $3.5M excluding fire alarm ($120,000); Sub B bids $3.7M including everything. After leveling, which is the low bid?",opts:["Sub A at $3.5M (apparent low)","Sub B at $3.7M is leveled low (Sub A leveled = $3.62M)","Both are equal","Sub A is still lower even after leveling"],a:1,exp:"Sub A leveled = $3.5M + $120K = $3.62M. Sub B = $3.7M. Sub B is $80,000 cheaper on a leveled basis despite appearing $200,000 higher in the raw bid."},{q:"A scope gap between HVAC and electrical subs is discovered after award. Who is financially responsible for the uncovered work?",opts:["The owner pays for all scope gaps","Whichever sub the GC can argue included it","The GC typically bears the gap risk and must resolve it through subcontract modification or absorb the cost","The gap work is simply not done"],a:2,exp:"The GC is responsible to the owner for complete project delivery. Scope gaps between subs that weren't closed at bid time become the GC's problem — a change order to the owner is often unrecoverable if the gap was foreseeable."},{q:"An exclusion in a bid means:",opts:["The item will be done for free","The bidder has explicitly stated this item is NOT included in their price","The item requires owner approval","The exclusion is automatically covered by another sub"],a:1,exp:"An exclusion is the bidder's clear statement that a specific item is not in their price. The GC must ensure every exclusion is either reassigned to another sub or added back to the excluding sub's scope."},{q:"Why might a low bid be suspicious in a bid leveling analysis?",opts:["Low bids always indicate fraud","A very low bid may reflect missed scope, aggressive assumptions, or extensive exclusions — requiring careful leveling to confirm it's truly comparable","Low bids should be awarded immediately","Low bids always win on public projects"],a:1,exp:"A unusually low bid often means the sub missed scope or made unrealistic assumptions. Awarding without leveling invites scope disputes and change orders later."},{q:"An allowance of $50,000 for specialty hardware is in a subcontract. The actual hardware costs $58,000. What happens?",opts:["The sub absorbs the $8,000 difference","A $8,000 change order reconciles the actual cost against the allowance","The GC pays $58,000 with no adjustment","The owner selects cheaper hardware to stay within the allowance"],a:1,exp:"Allowances are reconciled to actual cost. The $8,000 overage is formalized as a change order to ensure proper accounting and owner notification."},{q:"A unit price schedule in a subcontract is most useful for:",opts:["Establishing the initial contract price","Enabling rapid change order pricing for foreseeable scope additions or deletions without re-negotiation","Setting the bid bond amount","Calculating retainage"],a:1,exp:"Unit price schedules pre-agree prices for likely change types (e.g., additional concrete, extra framing), enabling fast, fair change order pricing when scope changes occur."},{q:"An additive alternate bid is:",opts:["A deduction from the base bid","A separate price for additional scope that the owner may elect to add after seeing the base bid price","A required part of every bid","A bid adjustment for inflation"],a:1,exp:"An additive alternate is an option the owner priced separately: if the base bid is within budget, the owner can add the alternate scope for the additional alternate price."},{q:"During bid leveling of 4 concrete bids, the GC finds that Sub C's bid excludes reinforcing steel. How should this be handled?",opts:["Disqualify Sub C immediately","Add the cost of reinforcing steel to Sub C's leveled price for comparison, and clarify whether Sub C will include it at award","Accept Sub C as-is — low bids win","Contact the other subs to exclude rebar too"],a:1,exp:"Add the missing scope (rebar) to Sub C's price to level fairly, then decide on award. At award, Sub C's scope must be clarified to include rebar — no scope gaps left in the awarded subcontract."},{q:'What is a "bid qualification" in the context of bid leveling?',opts:["The sub's license number",'A condition or clarification a bidder attaches to their price that may change the basis of comparison (e.g., "price based on 14-week schedule assumption")',"The bid bond","The sub's insurance certificate"],a:1,exp:'Bid qualifications are conditions attached to a price. A sub might qualify: "price based on uninterrupted access to zone 3" — if that condition is not met, their price changes. Qualifications must be identified and resolved in leveling.'},{q:"Three leveling scenarios: Sub A = $4.5M (includes everything); Sub B = $4.1M (excludes $250K of scope); Sub C = $4.3M (includes all scope, unit price schedule included). Which is the true low bid?",opts:["Sub B at $4.1M","Sub B leveled at $4.35M; Sub C at $4.3M is the leveled low fully-scoped bid","Sub A at $4.5M","Sub C because it has a unit price schedule"],a:1,exp:"Sub B leveled = $4.1M + $250K = $4.35M. Sub C at $4.3M (fully inclusive) is $50K lower than leveled Sub B. Sub C is the true low bid."},{q:"A GC receives 2 bids for electrical work: $1.85M and $3.2M — a 73% spread. What does this likely indicate?",opts:["The low bid is fraudulent","One sub likely missed significant scope; the GC should level both bids carefully and clarify scope with the low bidder before award","Normal bidding variation","The high bid is the correct price; award to low"],a:1,exp:"A 73% bid spread is a significant red flag. Either the low bidder missed scope or the high bidder over-scoped. Level both bids and clarify scope with the low bidder before awarding — large gaps often mean problems post-award."},{q:"What should be done with bid exclusions that are legitimately not within any sub's scope?",opts:["Leave them out of the project","The GC must either self-perform the work, assign it to a sub by change to their scope, or add a separate subcontract","Issue a change order to the owner proactively","Exclude them from the GMP"],a:1,exp:"Every item required for a complete project must be covered by someone. Uncovered scope becomes an unplanned cost — the GC must close all gaps before finalizing the GMP or project budget."},{q:"Why is bid leveling particularly important in a hard-market bidding environment?",opts:["Subs bid more carefully in hard markets","In competitive markets, subs may cut scope, use aggressive exclusions, or reduce allowances to win bids — making leveling essential to avoid hidden gaps that emerge during construction","Bid leveling is more important in slow markets","Hard markets produce identical bids"],a:1,exp:"In competitive markets, subs sharpen pencils aggressively — sometimes by reducing scope inclusions rather than genuine efficiency. Careful leveling protects the GC from awarding a low bid that's missing significant scope."},{q:'An "alternate bid" must be:',opts:["Included in every bid package","Clearly defined in the bid documents with specific scope — allowing the owner to compare base + alternate vs. base alone","Submitted separately from the base bid","Only used on public projects"],a:1,exp:"Alternates must be precisely defined in the bid package: what scope is added/deleted, how it will be incorporated into the base contract if accepted, and the deadline for acceptance."},{q:"How does a bid leveling matrix help the GC make award decisions?",opts:["It ranks bids automatically","It organizes all bids in a common format, showing inclusions, exclusions, allowances, and leveled totals side-by-side — enabling an informed, defensible award decision","It replaces the need for scope review","It calculates the contractor's profit margin"],a:1,exp:"A well-organized leveling matrix documents the complete comparison, supports the award rationale, and provides a paper trail if the award decision is ever questioned."},{q:`A sub's bid includes a $40,000 allowance for "misc. concrete patching." When should this allowance be questioned?`,opts:["Never — allowances are standard","When the scope of patching is determinable from the drawings; an allowance for definable scope suggests the sub didn't take off the actual quantity","Only if the amount seems high","Only on public projects"],a:1,exp:"Allowances for determinable scope items suggest the sub didn't fully price the work — or is using an allowance to hide a gap. The GC should clarify what's included and require a firm price if the scope is defined in the drawings."},{q:"The leveled low bid for a subcontract is $2.1M. The second-low leveled bid is $2.08M. How should the GC approach the award?",opts:["Always award to the absolute lowest leveled price","Award to the $2.08M sub (true low); but also consider qualifications, track record, and financial strength — a $20K difference may not justify awarding to an unfamiliar sub","Re-bid with 3 more subs","Award to the $2.1M sub for being more conservative"],a:1,exp:"Bid leveling identifies the most competitive price, but award decisions weigh multiple factors: price, track record, bonding capacity, schedule capability, and relationship. A $20K difference is less than 1% and may not outweigh qualitative factors."},{q:'What is a "scope exclusion matrix" used for in GMP preparation?',opts:["Recording excluded alternates","Documenting all subcontractor exclusions and clarifications for owner review — confirming the GC and owner agree on what is and isn't included in the GMP","Setting unit prices","Calculating the contractor's overhead"],a:1,exp:"A scope exclusion matrix attached to the GMP lists every subcontractor exclusion, clarification, and allowance, ensuring the owner sees and acknowledges what's included — reducing disputes about GMP scope post-award."},{q:"What does it mean when multiple subs exclude the same item from their bids?",opts:["The item is optional","The item is likely in the GC's scope, specified by someone else, or a genuine scope gap — and must be immediately resolved to avoid a missing-scope change order","The item should be deleted from the project","It validates the exclusion"],a:1,exp:"When multiple subs exclude the same item, it signals either a specification gap, a scope item assigned to the GC's self-perform, or a genuine project gap. The GC must resolve responsibility before the GMP is set."}]},5:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Aug 4",title:"Session 1 — CPM Basics: Activities, Logic Links & Float"},{day:"Wed Aug 6",title:"Session 2 — Critical Path Identification & What Delays the Project"},{day:"Thu Aug 7",title:"Session 3 — Schedule Compression: Crashing & Fast-Tracking"},{day:"Fri Aug 8",title:"Session 4 — Schedule Workshop: Build a CPM for a SoCal Office Project"}],vocabulary:[{term:"CPM",full:"Critical Path Method",definition:"A scheduling technique that models all project activities, their durations, and logical dependencies (predecessors/successors) to identify the longest path through the project network — the critical path — which determines the minimum project duration. Any delay to a critical path activity delays the project completion.",example:"The CPM schedule for the 18-story office tower identified a critical path of 480 days through foundation → core → structure → exterior skin → MEP rough-in → finishes; the schedule used Primavera P6 with 1,240 activities."},{term:"CRITICAL PATH",full:"Critical Path",definition:"The longest sequence of dependent activities in the project schedule, determining the minimum project duration. Activities on the critical path have zero float — any delay directly extends the project completion date. The critical path can shift as activities are delayed or accelerated.",example:"Structural steel was on the critical path; a 2-week steel fabrication delay pushed the overall project completion from October 15 to October 29 — and the GC's LD exposure began."},{term:"TOTAL FLOAT",full:"Total Float (Schedule Float)",definition:"The amount of time a non-critical activity can be delayed without delaying the project completion. Total Float = Latest Start − Early Start (or Latest Finish − Early Finish). Activities with zero total float are on the critical path. Float is a project resource — owner-caused delays can consume float, potentially converting non-critical activities to critical.",example:"Interior finishes had 15 days of total float; when an owner RFI caused a 10-day delay on finishes, the critical path was not affected — 5 days of float remained."},{term:"PREDECESSOR",full:"Predecessor Activity",definition:"An activity that must be completed (or start) before a successor activity can begin. The logical relationship between activities defines the project network. Common logic types: Finish-to-Start (FS — most common), Start-to-Start (SS), Finish-to-Finish (FF). Missing predecessor logic is a common scheduling error.",example:'In the schedule, "pour foundation" was a finish-to-start predecessor to "erect structural steel" — steel could not begin until the foundation pour was complete and cured.'},{term:"BASELINE SCHEDULE",full:"Baseline Project Schedule",definition:"The owner-approved original project schedule against which actual performance is measured. The baseline is frozen at contract execution; it becomes the reference for delay claims, float analysis, and schedule impact assessments. Updates show actual vs. baseline progress; the baseline itself is not changed without owner approval.",example:"The baseline schedule showed a 450-day project duration starting January 15; the monthly schedule update as of day 90 showed the project was 5 days behind baseline on structural steel."},{term:"LOOK-AHEAD SCHEDULE",full:"3-Week / 6-Week Look-Ahead Schedule",definition:"A short-interval schedule (typically 3–6 weeks) showing detailed activities for the near-term construction window. Prepared weekly by the superintendent, the look-ahead identifies immediate constraints (material deliveries, inspections, access) and enables proactive problem-solving before delays occur. More actionable than the overall CPM schedule.",example:"The superintendent's 3-week look-ahead identified that the waterproofing inspection was scheduled for Tuesday but the inspector wasn't available until Thursday — allowing a 2-day schedule adjustment without impacting the CPM."}],quiz:[{q:"What is the critical path in a CPM schedule?",opts:["The fastest possible schedule","The longest sequence of dependent activities determining the minimum project duration — any delay extends completion","The most expensive activities in the schedule","The path with the most float"],a:1,exp:"The critical path is the longest duration path through the activity network. It defines how long the project must take; there is no float on critical path activities."},{q:"An activity has 0 days of total float. This means:",opts:["The activity can be delayed freely","The activity is on the critical path — any delay directly delays project completion","The activity is ahead of schedule","The activity has been completed"],a:1,exp:"Zero float = critical path activity. Any delay to this activity directly pushes the project completion date, potentially triggering liquidated damages."},{q:"An owner-caused delay consumes all 10 days of float on an activity. What is the consequence?",opts:["No consequence — float is there to be used","The activity is now on the critical path; any further delay to it directly delays project completion, and the GC has grounds to claim additional time","The GC must accelerate at its own cost","The contract time is automatically extended"],a:1,exp:"Float is a project resource; consuming it through owner-caused delays is a compensable event. When owner actions burn a contractor's float, the GC can claim time extension and potentially delay damages."},{q:'What is the relationship type between "pour foundation" and "erect structural steel" in most construction schedules?',opts:["Start-to-Start (SS)","Finish-to-Start (FS) — steel cannot begin until foundation is complete","Finish-to-Finish (FF)","No logical relationship"],a:1,exp:"Finish-to-Start (FS) is the most common relationship in construction: the predecessor must finish before the successor can start. Foundation pour must be complete before steel erection begins."},{q:"The baseline schedule shows a 400-day project. The current update shows 415 days remaining at day 30. What does this indicate?",opts:["Project is on schedule","Project is 15 days behind baseline — the CPM has slipped, and the team should investigate the cause","The baseline needs updating","Lender approval is needed"],a:1,exp:"A 15-day slippage at day 30 means the project is tracking behind baseline. The superintendent and PM must identify the causing activity, assess float, and determine if recovery is possible."},{q:'What is "crashing" a schedule?',opts:["Stopping work on a project","Compressing schedule duration by adding resources (more workers, overtime, multiple shifts) to critical path activities — at added cost","Removing activities from the critical path by re-sequencing","Deleting scope to shorten the schedule"],a:1,exp:"Crashing adds resources to critical path activities to shorten their duration, buying time at a cost. The GC evaluates: does the cost of crashing exceed the LD exposure avoided?"},{q:"Which type of schedule delay is the most problematic for a GC?",opts:["Excusable, compensable delay (owner-caused)","Non-excusable delay (GC-caused)","Excusable, non-compensable delay (weather)","Concurrent delay"],a:1,exp:"Non-excusable (GC-caused) delay is the worst outcome: the GC is responsible for LDs, cannot recover delay costs from the owner, and must absorb the schedule impact."},{q:"A look-ahead schedule is prepared:",opts:["Once at project start and not updated","Weekly by the superintendent for the next 3–6 weeks, identifying near-term constraints and enabling proactive problem-solving","Monthly by the PM for owner reporting","By the scheduler only"],a:1,exp:"The look-ahead schedule is the superintendent's primary weekly planning tool — a short-interval schedule (3–6 weeks) that translates the CPM into actionable daily work plans and identifies imminent constraints."},{q:"Three activities are on the critical path: A (15 days), B (20 days), C (10 days). What is the minimum path duration?",opts:["10 days","15 days","45 days","20 days"],a:2,exp:"Critical path activities are sequential (FS logic): 15 + 20 + 10 = 45 days minimum path duration."},{q:"An activity with 20 days of total float has its early start delayed by 15 days due to an RFI. What is the remaining float?",opts:["20 days","5 days","15 days","0 days"],a:1,exp:"20 days float − 15 days delay consumed = 5 days of remaining float. The activity has not become critical yet but has reduced buffer."},{q:"What is the baseline schedule used for during a delay claim?",opts:["Setting the GMP","Comparing as-planned vs. as-built to quantify delay: how much did an event push the schedule vs. the original plan?","Calculating subcontractor payment","Setting milestones only"],a:1,exp:'The baseline is the "as-planned" reference. Delay claims compare as-planned (baseline) to as-built (actual) to quantify the impact of specific delay events on project completion.'},{q:"Fast-tracking a schedule means:",opts:["Paying overtime to accelerate critical path work","Overlapping normally sequential phases — starting construction on completed early packages while later design or construction phases are still in progress","Running the schedule faster in the CPM software","Eliminating float from the schedule"],a:1,exp:"Fast-tracking overlaps phases that would normally be sequential. Risk: changes to earlier work (design, foundation) while later work is in progress can cause expensive rework."},{q:"A project has 30 days of weather float built into the baseline. An early winter causes 35 days of rain delays. How many days of excusable time extension is the GC entitled to?",opts:["35 days","30 days","5 days (net of float already included)","0 days — weather is always non-excusable"],a:2,exp:"The baseline already includes 30 days of weather float. Only delays beyond the included float are entitled to time extension: 35 − 30 = 5 days excusable delay extension."},{q:'What is a "schedule recovery plan"?',opts:["A plan to reduce project scope","A documented strategy showing how the project will recover from a delay and achieve the original or revised completion date","A request for additional GMP","A subcontractor termination notice"],a:1,exp:"When a project falls behind, a schedule recovery plan identifies specific actions (crashing, re-sequencing, added resources) to recover lost time — required by many contracts when project delays exceed a threshold."},{q:"The GC's superintendent is responsible for the look-ahead schedule because:",opts:["The PM has no field knowledge","The superintendent has direct knowledge of field conditions, crew availability, material deliveries, and upcoming constraints — enabling realistic short-interval planning","The contract requires the superintendent to write all schedules","The look-ahead replaces the CPM"],a:1,exp:"The superintendent's ground-level knowledge of what's actually happening (and likely to happen) in the field makes them the best person to maintain the 3–6 week look-ahead schedule."},{q:"What is concurrent delay and why is it legally complex?",opts:["Two activities running at the same time","When both the owner and contractor cause delays to the same period — courts struggle to apportion time and cost when both parties share responsibility","A schedule with two critical paths","Overtime work on two activities simultaneously"],a:1,exp:"Concurrent delay occurs when owner-caused and contractor-caused delays overlap. Legal treatment varies: some jurisdictions deny any recovery to either party; others attempt to apportion responsibility — highly complex in practice."},{q:"What is the predecessor-successor relationship in a CPM schedule?",opts:["All activities start simultaneously","An activity's logic link: a predecessor must be (finish/start) before a successor can begin/start — defining the network of dependencies","Activities are sorted by cost","The first and last activities in the schedule"],a:1,exp:"Predecessor-successor logic creates the project network. Without accurate logic links, the CPM cannot correctly compute the critical path or activity float."},{q:"A contractor receives a design change from the owner on a non-critical activity with 12 days of float. The design change adds 8 days of work to that activity. What is the schedule impact?",opts:["8-day project delay","4 days of float remain — no project delay","The critical path shifts to this activity","12-day delay"],a:1,exp:"12 days float − 8 days added work = 4 days float remaining. No critical path impact — the project completion date is not affected."},{q:"What does P6 (Primavera P6) refer to in construction?",opts:["A building code section","Oracle Primavera P6, the industry-standard CPM scheduling software for complex construction projects","A CSI Division","A type of structural connector"],a:1,exp:"Primavera P6 is the most widely used CPM scheduling software for large commercial and public construction projects, supporting complex logic, resource loading, and cost integration."},{q:"When is it economically rational to crash a schedule?",opts:["Never — crashing always costs more than it saves","When the cost of crashing is less than the LD exposure from completing late — or when the owner will pay for acceleration","Only when the owner requests it","When subcontractors are available at no added cost"],a:1,exp:"Crashing makes economic sense when crash cost < LD avoided. At $5,000/day LDs and $3,000/day crash cost, the GC saves $2,000/day — crashing is justified."}]},6:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Aug 11",title:"Session 1 — RFIs: Purpose, Process & Common Pitfalls"},{day:"Wed Aug 13",title:"Session 2 — Submittals: Log, Sequence & Critical Path Management"},{day:"Thu Aug 14",title:"Session 3 — ASIs, RFIs vs Change Orders: Managing Information Flow"},{day:"Fri Aug 15",title:"Session 4 — RFI/Submittal Workshop: Managing a Backlog Simulation"}],vocabulary:[{term:"RFI",full:"Request for Information",definition:"A formal written question from the contractor to the design team requesting clarification, interpretation, or additional information about the contract documents. RFIs are numbered and logged; responses are binding design interpretations. RFIs that change scope or cost must be followed by a change order.",example:"RFI #187 asked whether the structural engineer intended #5 or #6 rebar in the wall footing — the engineer's response (specification of #6) added $28,000 in material cost and generated Change Order #42."},{term:"SUBMITTAL",full:"Submittal / Submittal Item",definition:"Documents prepared by the contractor, subcontractor, or manufacturer submitted to the design team for review. Types include: shop drawings, product data, samples, test reports, and O&M manuals. Submittals confirm that proposed materials and methods conform to design intent. Late submittals are a primary cause of construction delays.",example:"The structural steel shop drawings (submittal #45) required 21-day design team review; submitted on March 1, approved with comments on March 22; revised submittal approved April 4 — just in time for the April 7 steel fabrication start."},{term:"SUBMITTAL LOG",full:"Submittal Log / Submittal Register",definition:"A comprehensive tracking register of every required submittal: submittal number, description, required date, date submitted, review period, review status, and resubmittal dates. The submittal log is a project management tool for tracking approval status and identifying critical-path submittals that could delay construction.",example:"The PM's submittal log showed 14 open items; 3 were on the critical path (curtain wall, elevator, rooftop MEP); all three were flagged RED for immediate action to prevent construction delays."},{term:"ARCHITECT'S SUPPLEMENTAL INSTRUCTION",full:"Architect's Supplemental Instruction (ASI)",definition:"A written instruction from the architect that clarifies or supplements the contract documents without changing the contract sum or time. ASIs handle minor design clarifications, finish selections, and coordination details. If an ASI changes scope or cost, it must be converted to a formal change order. AIA G710 is the standard ASI form.",example:"ASI #14 changed the lobby floor tile from 12×12 to 24×24 format at no cost change; the GC incorporated the ASI into the tile subcontract scope and updated the submittal log."},{term:"PRODUCT DATA",full:"Product Data Submittal",definition:"Manufacturer's specifications, technical data, installation instructions, and performance data for products to be incorporated into the work. Product data submittals are reviewed by the design team to confirm the proposed product meets specification requirements before installation. Required for all major specified products.",example:"The HVAC contractor submitted product data for the rooftop units (3 pages of manufacturer cut sheets and performance data); the mechanical engineer reviewed and approved the units as conforming to the specification."},{term:"REVIEW TURNAROUND",full:"Submittal Review Turnaround Period",definition:'The contractually specified time period the design team has to review and respond to submittals. AIA A201 specifies a "reasonable" time; many contracts define 10–21 days. Critical path submittals should be flagged and often have expedited review provisions. Late review responses can be the basis for schedule impact claims.',example:"The contract specified a 14-day submittal review period; the structural engineer's 28-day response on the critical-path steel shop drawings created a 14-day delay, supporting the GC's time extension request."}],quiz:[{q:"What is the primary purpose of an RFI?",opts:["To change the contract price","To obtain formal written clarification, interpretation, or additional information about the contract documents from the design team","To notify the owner of a delay","To submit shop drawings for approval"],a:1,exp:"RFIs are the contractor's formal mechanism for obtaining binding written answers to questions about design intent, conflicts, or ambiguities in the contract documents."},{q:"An RFI response results in additional scope. What must happen next?",opts:["Nothing — RFI responses automatically adjust the contract","The RFI must be followed by a formal change order to adjust the contract sum and/or time","The subcontractor absorbs the cost","The owner verbally approves the cost"],a:1,exp:"RFI responses that change scope, cost, or time must be formalized through the change order process. The RFI documents the design decision; the CO documents the contractual adjustment."},{q:'What is a "critical path submittal"?',opts:["A submittal for the most expensive item","A submittal where delayed review will directly delay a critical path activity — potentially pushing project completion and triggering LDs","A submittal submitted on the critical path date","A submittal approved by the owner"],a:1,exp:"Critical path submittals must be identified early and tracked closely. If the shop drawing for structural steel (critical path) isn't approved in time for fabrication to start, the whole project slips."},{q:"What is the difference between an RFI and an ASI?",opts:["They are identical","An RFI is a contractor question; an ASI is the architect's supplemental instruction clarifying/supplementing the documents — typically in response to an RFI or proactively","ASIs always change scope; RFIs never do","RFIs are only for structural issues"],a:1,exp:"RFIs ask questions; ASIs provide answers or additional direction. An ASI clarifies design intent without changing the contract sum or time. If the clarification creates a cost change, an ASI is converted to a change order."},{q:"The submittal log shows 8 open submittals overdue for review. What is the PM's first step?",opts:["Ignore and wait for the design team","Escalate immediately: contact the design team, prioritize critical path items, and document the outstanding review requests with dates","Submit more RFIs","Issue a default notice to the design team"],a:1,exp:"Overdue submittals need immediate escalation. The PM must contact the design team, prioritize by schedule criticality, and document all follow-up to support a potential delay claim if submittals continue to be late."},{q:"What type of submittal requires the most detailed review by the structural engineer?",opts:["Product data","Shop drawings for structural steel connections","Color samples","O&M manuals"],a:1,exp:"Structural steel shop drawings require the most intensive engineer review — each connection must match the engineer's design intent and loading assumptions. These are life-safety critical submittals."},{q:"A contractor submits shop drawings 5 days after the required submittal date. The design team takes 14 days (contract standard) to review. How many days of potential schedule impact did the late submission create?",opts:["0 days — 14 days is the standard review period","5 days — the late submission shifted the review completion by 5 days","19 days","14 days"],a:1,exp:"The contractor submitted 5 days late; review completion is now 5 days later than if submitted on time. If this submittal is on the critical path, the project has a 5-day schedule risk — caused by the contractor's late submission."},{q:"An RFI response clarifies a detail that will require 3 additional days of work on a non-critical activity with 8 days of float. What is the schedule impact?",opts:["3-day project delay","No project delay — 5 days of float remain","The activity is now on the critical path","8-day delay"],a:1,exp:"8 days float − 3 days added work = 5 days remaining float. No critical path impact. If this RFI response required > 8 days of additional work, it would push the activity to the critical path."},{q:"What information should every line item in a submittal log include?",opts:["Only the submittal number","Submittal number, description, CSI spec section, required submission date, actual submission date, days in review, status, and follow-up notes","Only submission date and status","Subcontractor name only"],a:1,exp:"A comprehensive submittal log enables schedule management: tracking every required submittal with submission deadlines, review durations, and status allows proactive management of critical path risks."},{q:'When a contractor marks an RFI as "impacting schedule," what should be included in the RFI?',opts:["Only the question","A description of the schedule impact, identification of the affected activity and its float, and a request for response by a specific date","Legal threats","Just the submittal number"],a:1,exp:"Schedule-impacting RFIs must document the impact clearly: which activity is affected, how much float remains, and the date by which a response is needed to avoid schedule impact — building the documentary foundation for a delay claim if needed."},{q:"ASIs that change the contract sum must be:",opts:["Issued as a revised ASI","Converted to a change order or PCO — ASIs are limited to scope clarifications that don't change price or time","Accepted as part of general conditions","Submitted to CDLAC"],a:1,exp:"ASIs are for no-cost, no-time clarifications. When the architectural direction changes scope, cost, or time, the change must be formalized as a change order — not an ASI."},{q:"A contractor receives 12 RFIs in one week from the design team (unusual). What does this pattern suggest?",opts:["Everything is going smoothly","The design documents have significant issues — conflicts, omissions, or ambiguities — requiring formal resolution","The design team is very responsive","The contractor is causing problems"],a:1,exp:"A surge in design-team-generated RFIs (design team issuing to contractor is unusual — usually contractor issues to design team) or a surge of contractor RFIs signals document quality problems that may impact schedule and cost."},{q:"What is product data different from shop drawings?",opts:["They are identical","Product data is manufacturer-published technical information for a standard product; shop drawings are custom fabrication drawings prepared by the contractor/fabricator for project-specific elements","Product data is submitted by the owner","Shop drawings only apply to structural elements"],a:1,exp:"Product data = catalog/cut sheets from the manufacturer for standard products. Shop drawings = custom fabrication drawings for project-specific elements (structural steel connections, custom millwork, precast panels)."},{q:'What is a "2nd review" (resubmittal) and when is it required?',opts:["Required for all submittals",'Required when the first submission was "Revise and Resubmit" — the contractor must address reviewer comments and resubmit for a second approval',"Required by the building department","Only required for structural submittals"],a:1,exp:'When the design team returns a submittal marked "Revise and Resubmit," the contractor must address all comments and resubmit. This adds review cycle time — typically another 7–14 days — with direct schedule impact if on the critical path.'},{q:"What is the purpose of tracking RFI response times in the project log?",opts:["Optional administrative record only","To identify slow responders, support schedule impact claims for delayed responses, and ensure accountability for design team responsiveness","Required by insurance only","Only needed for lender reporting"],a:1,exp:"RFI response time tracking is essential for delay claims: if design team responses take 45 days vs. the 14-day contract standard, the GC has documented support for a time extension claim."},{q:'A submittal is returned "Approved as Noted." What does this mean for the contractor?',opts:["The submittal requires complete revision and resubmittal","The submittal is approved but has reviewer comments that must be incorporated — the contractor can proceed with fabrication incorporating the noted corrections","The submittal is rejected","Full approval without any comments"],a:1,exp:'"Approved as Noted" means the design team approves the submittal subject to incorporation of reviewer comments. The contractor can proceed with fabrication or ordering, but must incorporate the noted corrections.'},{q:"Late design team submittal reviews are a basis for the GC to claim:",opts:["Nothing — design teams have no time requirements","Schedule time extension and potentially delay damages if the late review directly delayed a critical path activity","Extra overhead and profit automatically","Bond reduction"],a:1,exp:"When contractual review periods are exceeded and the late response impacts a critical path activity, the GC can claim a schedule time extension and, if costs were incurred due to the delay, compensable delay damages."},{q:"How should a superintendent manage critical path submittals on a fast-moving project?",opts:["Submit them all at once at project start","Identify critical path submittals early, submit as early as possible, expedite reviewer follow-up, and track weekly until approved","Delegate entirely to the GC PM","Wait for the design team to request submittals"],a:1,exp:"Critical path submittals need maximum lead time and aggressive follow-up. The superintendent must know which submittals are on the critical path and ensure early submission and expedited review."},{q:'An RFI asking "what color should the lobby accent wall be?" is:',opts:["A valid RFI","Not an appropriate RFI — finish selections are typically handled via submittal/sample process or ASI, not formal RFI","A change order","A standard industry practice"],a:1,exp:"RFIs are for technical clarifications, conflicts, and interpretations. Owner finish selections (colors, materials) are handled through the submittal/sample process — using the RFI system for routine selections clogs the information management process."},{q:"A well-maintained submittal log helps a GC:",opts:["Eliminate all submittals","Proactively manage approval timelines, prevent critical path delays, and document the design team's review performance — a project management and dispute prevention tool","Reduce the number of RFIs","Satisfy lender requirements only"],a:1,exp:"The submittal log is a proactive management tool: tracking what's out for review, how long it's been out, and what's coming up — enabling the PM to prevent approval delays before they impact the schedule."}]}},t={7:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Aug 18",title:"Session 1 — Subcontract Agreement Structure & Key Clauses"},{day:"Wed Aug 20",title:"Session 2 — Retainage, Pay-When-Paid & Cash Flow Management"},{day:"Thu Aug 21",title:"Session 3 — Performance Bonds & Notice-to-Cure Process"},{day:"Fri Aug 22",title:"Session 4 — Subcontract Risk Workshop: Redlining a Problem Sub Agreement"}],vocabulary:[{term:"SUBCONTRACT AGREEMENT",full:"Subcontract Agreement",definition:"The written contract between the GC and a subcontractor defining scope, price, schedule, insurance requirements, and risk allocation. The subcontract must flow down relevant prime contract obligations and is the primary tool for GC risk management with subcontractors. AIA A401 is the standard subcontract form.",example:"The $3.2M electrical subcontract (AIA A401 modified) included: the scope exhibit, 10% retainage, 45-day payment terms after GC receives owner payment, and a 7-day cure period for performance defaults."},{term:"SCOPE EXHIBIT",full:"Subcontract Scope Exhibit",definition:`An attachment to the subcontract that specifically defines the sub's scope of work, exclusions, and assumptions. The scope exhibit closes scope gaps and prevents "I thought you were doing that" disputes during construction. A well-written scope exhibit is the GC's most important risk management tool in subcontract administration.`,example:"The MEP scope exhibit for the mechanical sub identified 8 exclusions (fire sprinklers by others, controls by electrical sub, commissioning by owner) and 3 inclusions clarified from the bid leveling (including roof drain connections)."},{term:"RETAINAGE",full:"Contract Retainage",definition:"A percentage of each progress payment withheld by the owner from the GC (and by the GC from subs) as security for project completion. Typically 10% through 50% completion, then reduced to 5% (or released on subcontracts at substantial completion of that scope). California statutes regulate retainage on public projects.",example:"The subcontract held 10% retainage; when the electrician reached 50% completion with satisfactory performance, the GC reduced retainage to 5% per the contract terms, releasing $95,000 to improve the sub's cash flow."},{term:"PAY-WHEN-PAID",full:"Pay-When-Paid Clause",definition:"A subcontract provision conditioning the GC's obligation to pay a sub on first receiving payment from the owner. California courts have significantly limited pay-when-paid enforceability: it cannot delay payment indefinitely or transfer owner insolvency risk to subs on private projects. After 35 days from a proper invoice, payment is due regardless.",example:"The subcontract's pay-when-paid clause was tested when the owner delayed payment for 60 days; California law required the GC to pay the sub by day 35 regardless of owner payment status."},{term:"PERFORMANCE BOND",full:"Subcontractor Performance Bond",definition:"A surety bond guaranteeing a subcontractor's performance of its subcontract. Required by GCs on high-risk or large-value subcontracts. If the sub defaults, the GC (obligee) can make a bond claim; the surety must investigate and either arrange completion or pay the penal sum. Bonds typically cost 1–3% of subcontract value.",example:"The GC required performance bonds on all subcontracts exceeding $500,000; the $1.8M mechanical subcontractor posted a bond at 1.5% cost ($27,000 premium) which protected the GC when the sub encountered financial difficulties mid-project."},{term:"NOTICE TO CURE",full:"Notice to Cure / Default Notice",definition:"A written notice from the GC to a defaulting subcontractor identifying the specific breach and demanding remedy within a specified period (typically 7 days under AIA-based subcontracts). The notice to cure is a contractual prerequisite to termination; a defective notice can invalidate subsequent termination and expose the GC to wrongful termination liability.",example:"The GC issued a 7-day Notice to Cure on August 5 after the framing sub's crew size dropped below contract requirements; the sub cured by mobilizing additional resources before August 12, avoiding termination."}],quiz:[{q:"What is the most important document for defining a subcontractor's scope of work?",opts:["The prime contract drawings","The scope exhibit attached to the subcontract","The bid invitation only","The payment schedule"],a:1,exp:'The scope exhibit specifically defines what the sub is required to do, their exclusions, and clarifications — it is the operative document for resolving "I thought you were doing that" scope disputes.'},{q:"Retainage serves what purpose for the GC?",opts:["Increases GC profit","Provides security for project completion — the withheld funds can be applied to deficiencies or completion cost if the sub fails to complete their work properly","Reduces the subcontract price","Is required by CEQA"],a:1,exp:"Retainage is a financial security mechanism: the GC retains a percentage of payments until the sub completes satisfactorily, ensuring the sub has an ongoing financial incentive to perform."},{q:"Under California law, how long can a pay-when-paid clause delay subcontractor payment?",opts:["Indefinitely until the GC is paid","No more than 35 days from a proper invoice, regardless of owner payment status","30 days only on public projects","Until the project is complete"],a:1,exp:"California Civil Code §8802 requires payment to subcontractors within 10 business days of GC receipt of owner payment. Case law limits pay-when-paid clauses so they cannot indefinitely delay payment or transfer owner insolvency risk to subs."},{q:"When should a GC require a performance bond from a subcontractor?",opts:["Never — bonds are too expensive","On high-risk, large-value subcontracts where default would significantly impact the project schedule or cost","On all subcontracts regardless of size","Only on public projects where required by law"],a:1,exp:"Performance bonds are valuable on high-risk subs (specialty trades, financial weak subs) and large-value scopes. The cost (1–3% of sub price) is weighed against the default risk and replacement cost."},{q:"What is the contractual prerequisite to terminating a subcontractor for default under most AIA-based subcontracts?",opts:["Verbal notice is sufficient","Written Notice to Cure identifying the specific breach and providing the cure period (typically 7 days)","A court order","Owner approval of the termination"],a:1,exp:"The Notice to Cure is the mandatory first step. Without proper written notice and a cure period, termination may be deemed wrongful, exposing the GC to breach of contract liability."},{q:"A subcontract allows 10% retainage. At $500,000 billed (out of $2M total), how much retainage has been withheld?",opts:["$200,000","$100,000","$50,000","$500,000"],a:2,exp:"10% × $500,000 billed = $50,000 retainage withheld. The sub has received $450,000 on $500,000 billed."},{q:"The subcontract flow-down provision requires:",opts:["The sub to sign the prime contract","The subcontract to incorporate relevant prime contract obligations — ensuring the GC's obligations to the owner flow down to the appropriate subs","The owner to approve all subcontracts","The sub to carry the same insurance as the GC"],a:1,exp:"Flow-down provisions pass prime contract obligations to subs (schedule, safety, document requirements, dispute resolution). Without flow-down, subs may not be bound by obligations the GC made to the owner."},{q:"A sub's performance bond cost is 1.5% of a $1.2M subcontract. What is the premium?",opts:["$12,000","$18,000","$24,000","$1,500"],a:1,exp:"1.5% × $1,200,000 = $18,000 bond premium."},{q:"Why is the scope exhibit more important than the drawing set for defining subcontract scope?",opts:["The scope exhibit replaces all drawings","The drawings show what to build; the scope exhibit clarifies what the sub is and isn't responsible for — closing gaps, resolving overlaps, and documenting bid clarifications specific to this sub's contract","Drawings always win in disputes","The scope exhibit only applies to MEP trades"],a:1,exp:"Drawings show design intent, but multiple subs work from the same drawings. The scope exhibit resolves who does what — specifying exactly which items on the drawings are this sub's responsibility and what is excluded."},{q:"When retainage is reduced from 10% to 5% at 50% completion, what is the cash benefit to a sub on a $2M subcontract who has billed $1M?",opts:["$0 — no cash benefit","$50,000 released — the 5% reduction applies to amounts already billed","$100,000 released","$1,000,000 released"],a:1,exp:"Reduction from 10% to 5% on $1M billed: previously held $100K; now hold $50K. Releasing $50,000 improves the sub's cash flow by that amount."},{q:"A Notice to Cure sent by email only when the contract requires certified mail delivery is:",opts:["Fully valid","Potentially defective — improperly delivered notices may not start the cure clock or support valid termination","Valid only if the sub acknowledges it","Not required in California"],a:1,exp:"Notice provisions are strictly enforced. If the contract specifies certified mail and the GC sends email only, the notice may be legally ineffective, potentially voiding a subsequent termination."},{q:'What does "back-to-back" mean in subcontract negotiation?',opts:["Two consecutive subcontracts",`The subcontract mirrors the prime contract obligations — the sub is bound on "back-to-back" terms matching the GC's obligations to the owner`,"Two subs sharing a scope","Sequential payment terms"],a:1,exp:"Back-to-back means the subcontract incorporates the prime contract's terms: schedule, milestone dates, change order procedures, and dispute resolution. The sub is bound by the same rules as the GC in the prime."},{q:"Why might a sub want retainage reduced or released early (e.g., at substantial completion of their scope)?",opts:["To pay less tax","To improve cash flow — retainage is working capital they've earned but can't use; early release reduces financing cost and improves project economics","To reduce bond requirements","To avoid final inspection"],a:1,exp:"Retainage is essentially a zero-interest loan from the sub to the GC. Early release at scope substantial completion is fair compensation for completed, satisfactory work and reduces the sub's working capital burden."},{q:"A subcontract is for $800,000. The sub defaults at 60% complete, and the replacement cost is $380,000. What does the GC owe the defaulted sub?",opts:["Nothing — the sub defaulted","The earned value to date minus the replacement cost: (60% × $800K) − $380K = $480K − $380K = $100K owed to the sub","$800,000 (the original price)","$380,000 (the replacement cost)"],a:1,exp:"The GC owes the sub for completed work minus completion costs. 60% × $800K = $480K earned. $480K − $380K replacement cost = $100K net owed to the defaulted sub (less any other damages)."},{q:"AIA A401 is:",opts:["The prime contract between owner and GC","The standard subcontract agreement form between contractor and subcontractor","The CM-at-risk agreement","The design-build contract"],a:1,exp:"AIA A401 is the Standard Form of Agreement Between Contractor and Subcontractor — the counterpart to AIA A201 for the subcontract relationship."},{q:"What happens if a sub's work has a defect discovered after retainage is released?",opts:["The GC has no recourse","The GC can pursue the sub under the warranty obligations in the subcontract and, if necessary, sue for breach","Retainage covers all defects permanently","The owner bears the cost"],a:1,exp:"Retainage release doesn't waive warranty rights. Subcontracts include warranty periods (typically 1 year per AIA) during which the sub is obligated to correct defective work at no cost."},{q:'What is a "back-charge"?',opts:["A fee the sub charges the GC","A cost the GC deducts from a subcontractor's payment for work the GC performed that was the sub's responsibility (clean-up, safety violations, completion work)","A lender charge for late payment","A retainage increase"],a:1,exp:"A back-charge is a cost deduction from a sub's payment for work the GC had to do on the sub's behalf: cleaning up after them, fixing their safety violations, or completing their scope."},{q:"Why is a well-drafted scope exhibit the GC's best risk management tool in subcontract administration?",opts:["It reduces the need for insurance",'It prevents the most common and expensive construction disputes — "who was supposed to do that" — by documenting scope responsibility clearly at contract execution',"It replaces the need for RFIs","It eliminates retainage requirements"],a:1,exp:"Unclear scope leads to expensive disputes during construction. A clear scope exhibit, drafted after bid leveling, closes gaps before work starts — preventing change orders, delays, and litigation."},{q:"A GC receives a sub's August invoice for $120,000 on September 1. The owner pays the GC on September 25. When must the GC pay the sub?",opts:["October 31 — pay-when-paid applies","Within 10 business days of receiving owner payment (approximately October 9)","Only when the project is complete","Within 35 days of the sub's invoice, regardless of owner payment"],a:1,exp:"California Civil Code §8802 requires GCs to pay subs within 10 business days after receiving owner payment. GC received owner payment Sept 25; sub must be paid by approximately October 9."},{q:"What information should a Notice to Cure include?",opts:["Just the sub's name","The specific breach (with examples), the cure required, the cure deadline (typically 7 days from delivery), and the consequences of failure to cure (termination)","An offer to renegotiate the subcontract","A list of alternative subcontractors"],a:1,exp:"A valid Notice to Cure must specifically identify the breach, demand specific cure, state the cure period, and warn of termination consequences — generic notices may be legally insufficient."}]},8:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Aug 25",title:"Session 1 — Change Order Classification: Owner, Design Error, Field Condition"},{day:"Wed Aug 27",title:"Session 2 — Pricing Change Orders: T&M vs Lump Sum Pricing"},{day:"Thu Aug 28",title:"Session 3 — Notice Requirements & Constructive Change Claims"},{day:"Fri Aug 29",title:"Session 4 — Change Order Management Workshop: 10-CO Project Simulation"}],vocabulary:[{term:"CHANGE ORDER",full:"Change Order (CO)",definition:'A formal written agreement between the owner and GC modifying the contract scope, price, and/or time. A change order supersedes the original contract for the changed work. All change orders must be agreed and signed before the work is performed (in theory); "constructive changes" occur when work is directed without formal CO.',example:"Change Order #18 added $142,000 and 12 calendar days for owner-requested lobby expansion; both parties signed the CO before the expanded work began."},{term:"POTENTIAL CHANGE ORDER",full:"Potential Change Order (PCO)",definition:"An internal GC document that identifies a possible change before it becomes a formal change order. PCOs track all identified changes, their pricing status, and approval status. Managing the PCO log proactively enables the GC to price and present changes quickly rather than accumulating a backlog.",example:"The PM opened PCO #47 when the owner's architect issued ASI #22 for upgraded lobby lighting — PCO tracked the $28,000 cost and 0-day schedule impact through approval, becoming Change Order #22."},{term:"CHANGE ORDER REQUEST",full:"Change Order Request (COR)",definition:"The formal written request submitted by the GC to the owner/architect requesting a change order for additional cost or time. A COR includes: description of change, cause, time impact analysis, and pricing breakdown. CORs that are denied can become the basis for claims if the work was directed and performed.",example:"COR #33 requested $195,000 and 8 calendar days for owner-directed scope added after GMP; the architect accepted the 8-day extension but reduced the price to $172,000 after negotiation."},{term:"TIME-AND-MATERIALS",full:"Time-and-Materials (T&M) Change",definition:"A method of pricing change order work where the owner pays the GC's actual labor (burdened), material, equipment, and markup costs. T&M provides transparency but requires detailed daily records (T&M tickets signed daily by the owner's representative). T&M is used when scope is uncertain; lump sum is preferred when scope is defined.",example:"The owner directed emergency waterproofing repairs on T&M basis; the GC's crews worked 3 days at $8,500/day burdened labor + $12,000 materials + 15% markup = $40,175 total T&M change order."},{term:"CONSTRUCTIVE CHANGE",full:"Constructive Change",definition:"A change to the contract work directed by the owner's words or conduct (but without a formal change order) that requires the contractor to perform additional work or incur additional costs. Courts recognize constructive changes as entitling the contractor to compensation, even without a signed CO. Notice is typically required.",example:"The owner's construction representative verbally directed the GC to install additional blocking not shown in the drawings; the GC submitted a COR as a constructive change claim, supported by daily logs and the rep's email confirmation."},{term:"SCHEDULE IMPACT",full:"Change Order Schedule Impact",definition:"The effect of a change order on the project schedule, typically measured in added calendar days of contract time. Schedule impact must be analyzed for every change, not just price. Failure to claim schedule impact at the time of a change can waive the right to a time extension later.",example:"Change Order #9 added $85,000 for redesigned structural connections and a 14-day schedule extension; without the time extension, the 14-day added work would have made the GC 14 days late and exposed them to $140,000 in LDs."}],quiz:[{q:"Which of the following is NOT a typical cause for a change order?",opts:["Owner adds scope","Design error discovered during construction","Unforeseen site condition (differing site condition)","GC misread the drawings and bid too low"],a:3,exp:"A GC's bid error is the GC's responsibility — not a valid change order cause. Valid COs arise from changes in scope (owner direction), design errors the owner warrants, or unforeseen conditions beyond both parties' control."},{q:"What is the difference between a PCO and a formal change order?",opts:["They are identical","A PCO is the GC's internal tracking document for a potential change; a CO is the formal, signed agreement between owner and GC modifying the contract","PCOs only apply to owner-directed changes","COs require court approval"],a:1,exp:"PCO = internal tracking before owner agreement. CO = signed bilateral modification of the contract. The PCO becomes a CO when both parties agree to the pricing and scope."},{q:"What is a T&M change order and when is it appropriate?",opts:["A fixed-price change for time-sensitive work","Payment for actual labor + materials + markup — used when the scope is uncertain and a lump sum price cannot be established in advance","A type of contingency allowance","A performance incentive payment"],a:1,exp:"T&M is appropriate when scope is too uncertain to price as a lump sum. The owner pays actuals plus markup. Daily T&M tickets signed by the owner's rep are critical documentation."},{q:"Why is it critical to claim schedule impact at the time of a change order?",opts:["To reduce the CO price","Failure to claim time at the CO stage may waive the right to a time extension; the owner's signature on a CO without time is evidence that no time impact was claimed","To satisfy CEQA requirements","To trigger the RFI process"],a:1,exp:`Time impact must be claimed contemporaneously. A signed CO that says "no time impact" or doesn't mention time can be used to deny later schedule extension claims — even if the work did delay the project.`},{q:"A COR is submitted for a design error. The architect denies the COR, claiming the contractor should have caught the error. What is the GC's next step?",opts:["Accept the denial and absorb the cost","Escalate per the dispute resolution process (architect decision → mediation → arbitration), with documentation of the design error and its cost impact","Issue a stop-work notice","Contact the owner's lender"],a:1,exp:"A disputed COR follows the contract dispute resolution path. The GC preserves all rights by escalating per contract procedures, documenting the error's cost impact, and not simply absorbing unresolved claims."},{q:"A constructive change occurs when:",opts:["The owner signs a formal change order","The owner or their representative directs work beyond contract scope without issuing a formal change order — entitling the GC to compensation","The GC voluntarily adds scope","An RFI changes the scope"],a:1,exp:"Constructive changes are implied changes: owner direction that requires additional work but lacks the formal CO paperwork. Courts recognize these as compensable if properly documented and noticed."},{q:"What daily documentation is critical when performing T&M work?",opts:["Only the invoice at the end","T&M daily tickets signed by the owner's authorized representative, documenting hours, workers, equipment, and materials for each day's work","Just the GC's internal time records","Photographs only"],a:1,exp:"Unsigned or missing T&M tickets create payment disputes later. Owner-signed daily tickets are the contemporaneous, undisputable record of T&M cost — critical for change order payment."},{q:"A change order adds 8 days to the contract. How should the GC update the schedule?",opts:["No update needed","Issue a formal schedule update reflecting the 8-day extension, showing revised substantial and final completion dates — filed with the change order","Only update if the work is on the critical path","Update after construction is complete"],a:1,exp:"Each time-extension CO should be reflected in a schedule update showing the revised contract duration and completion dates. This documents the cumulative impact of all changes on the project timeline."},{q:"A GC estimates a lump sum CO at $45,000. The owner wants T&M to verify cost. The actual T&M cost comes in at $52,000. Who pays the difference?",opts:["GC pays — they offered lump sum","Owner pays — T&M is the agreed basis; actuals govern","Split 50/50 between owner and GC","Neither — the average of lump sum and T&M applies"],a:1,exp:"If T&M is agreed as the pricing basis, the owner pays actual cost + markup regardless of the GC's initial estimate. T&M is an actual-cost basis, not an estimate."},{q:"The notice requirement for change orders typically means:",opts:["The GC can wait until project end to submit all COs","The GC must notify the owner promptly (often within 7–21 days) after discovering a change — failure to provide timely notice can waive the right to compensation","Only written notices count; verbal is sufficient for urgent changes","Notice is only required for changes over $50,000"],a:1,exp:"Notice requirements protect the owner's ability to investigate, approve, or reject changes before significant cost is incurred. Failure to provide timely notice — as required by contract — can result in denial of a COR."},{q:'What is "cumulative impact" in change order management?',opts:["The total CO dollar amount","The impact of multiple changes on project efficiency beyond each change's individual cost — disruption, learning curve breaks, and productivity loss that is difficult to quantify","Schedule delay from a single large CO","The GC's markup on changes"],a:1,exp:"Individual changes may each appear manageable, but collectively they disrupt work sequences, trade coordination, and productivity. Cumulative impact (loss of productivity claim) is harder to prove but often the largest impact."},{q:"A change order is signed by the owner's authorized representative. Is this always valid?",opts:["Yes — any owner signature is valid","Only if the representative had authority to approve the change — GCs must verify that the person signing has contractual authority (check the contract's authorization clause)","No — only the owner's president can sign","Valid for changes under $10,000 only"],a:1,exp:"Change order authority is delegated by contract. If the owner's rep has a $25,000 approval limit and signs a $50,000 CO, the approval may be invalid. Verify authority limits before relying on signatures."},{q:"When pricing a lump sum change order, the GC should include:",opts:["Direct costs only","Direct costs + overhead + profit + schedule impact cost (extended GCs if applicable) + subcontractor COs for the same change","Material cost only","Labor cost only"],a:1,exp:"A complete CO pricing includes all affected costs: direct labor/material/equipment, overhead and profit markup, extended general conditions if the change adds schedule time, and all sub COs for the same scope change."},{q:'What is a "change order log" and why is it important?',opts:["A list of uninitiated PCOs only","A register tracking every PCO/COR/CO: number, description, status, amount, days, and approval date — providing a real-time picture of approved and pending contract modifications","Only required on public projects","A financial audit document"],a:1,exp:"The CO log is a project management tool: tracking the total contract modifications, pending COs, disputed items, and schedule impact provides the PM and owner real-time budget and schedule picture."},{q:"A differing site condition (DSC) is a valid change order cause when:",opts:["The GC should have anticipated it","Subsurface conditions materially differ from those indicated in the contract documents — allowing recovery of added cost and time","The GC did a thorough site investigation","DSCs only apply to public projects"],a:1,exp:"DSC clauses (AIA A201 §3.7.4) entitle the GC to cost and time recovery for subsurface conditions that differ materially from what was indicated in the contract documents — regardless of standard site investigation expectations."},{q:'Why should the GC track "pending COs" separately from "approved COs" in cost reporting?',opts:["No difference — all COs should be treated the same","Pending COs represent potential budget exposure; tracking them separately allows the owner to see the full budget picture including at-risk items not yet approved","Pending COs reduce retainage","Only relevant for LIHTC projects"],a:1,exp:"A complete cost forecast includes both approved contract adjustments and pending COs. Showing only approved COs understates the project's actual budget situation when significant changes are unresolved."},{q:`An owner's representative verbally tells the GC to "do whatever it takes" to fix a water intrusion problem. This is a:`,opts:["License to proceed without any documentation","Potential constructive change direction — the GC should confirm in writing, track T&M if cost is uncertain, and submit a formal COR as a constructive change","Not compensable without written authorization","Only valid for emergency work"],a:1,exp:'Verbal direction is risky — the GC should immediately confirm in writing ("per our conversation, we are proceeding with the following work..."), track costs on T&M, and submit a COR to formalize the compensation.'},{q:"What is the GC's markup on change orders typically composed of?",opts:["Only 10% flat","Overhead (field and home office) and profit, typically a combined 15–20% on the direct cost of the change","Just labor premium","Only bonding and insurance"],a:1,exp:"CO markup covers field overhead (superintendent time for the change), home office overhead (PM, accounting), and profit — typically 15–20% combined on direct cost, per the contract's overhead and profit provision."},{q:'The best defense against "oral change order" disputes is:',opts:["Always require signed COs before starting any work","Contemporaneous written confirmation of verbal directions, T&M tickets, and a proactive PCO/COR tracking system — combined with contract rights for implied changes","Refuse all verbal owner directions","Use video to record verbal directions"],a:1,exp:"Written confirmation of verbal direction, contemporaneous T&M records, and proactive COR submission create the paper trail needed if oral change disputes arise — even without a signed CO before work starts."}]},9:{sessions:[{day:"Tue Sep 2",title:"Session 1 — Job Cost Report Structure: Reading and Analyzing"},{day:"Wed Sep 3",title:"Session 2 — CTC & EAC: Forecasting to Completion"},{day:"Thu Sep 4",title:"Session 3 — Variance Analysis: Identifying Over/Under Budget Divisions"},{day:"Fri Sep 5",title:"Session 4 — Cost Forecast Workshop: Problem Project Recovery Plan"}],vocabulary:[{term:"COST-TO-COMPLETE",full:"Cost-to-Complete (CTC)",definition:"The estimated cost required to finish the remaining work in a project or cost code. CTC is the PM's forward-looking estimate, based on progress to date and remaining scope. When added to actual costs incurred, CTC produces the Estimate at Completion (EAC). Accurate CTC is the foundation of a reliable cost forecast.",example:"At 60% project complete, the PM estimated CTC of $8.2M for the remaining 40% of work; combined with $11.8M in actual costs to date = $20.0M EAC (vs. $19.5M budget — indicating a $500K overrun forecast)."},{term:"ESTIMATE AT COMPLETION",full:"Estimate at Completion (EAC)",definition:"The total forecasted project cost at completion: EAC = Actual Costs to Date + Cost-to-Complete. EAC is the single most important cost management metric — it tells the owner and GC whether the project will finish on budget. EAC should be updated monthly and presented with variance to original budget.",example:"Actuals to date: $7.3M. CTC: $13.1M. EAC: $20.4M. Original budget: $19.8M. Budget variance: −$600K (over budget). The PM prepared a corrective action plan to recover $400K through identified VE and subcontractor negotiations."},{term:"COMMITTED COST",full:"Committed Cost",definition:"The total cost obligated to date: actual invoices paid + approved subcontract/PO values for work not yet invoiced. Committed cost represents the maximum expenditure if no additional scope is added. It is higher than actual cost and is the best current indicator of total cost exposure for awarded scopes.",example:"The concrete subcontract was $2.8M (committed cost). The sub had billed and been paid $1.9M to date. Even though actuals were $1.9M, the full $2.8M was committed — reflected in the cost report."},{term:"BUDGET VARIANCE",full:"Budget Variance (Cost Variance)",definition:"The difference between the original budget (or approved budget including change orders) and the EAC. Budget Variance = Budget − EAC. Positive variance = under budget; negative variance = over budget. Variance analysis by cost code identifies where the project is trending over or under.",example:"Cost code 03.100 (Concrete) had a budget of $2.8M and EAC of $3.1M: a −$300K unfavorable variance caused by form rework from design changes and one DSC pour."},{term:"CASH FLOW PROJECTION",full:"Project Cash Flow Projection",definition:"A month-by-month forecast of project expenditures and revenues (billings), showing when money flows in and out of the project. Cash flow projections help the GC manage working capital, identify when the project will be cash-negative, and optimize billing timing. Required by most construction lenders.",example:"The cash flow projection showed a peak negative cash position of $1.8M in month 6 (before a large billing was expected), informing the GC to increase its working capital line of credit before that period."},{term:"COST FORECAST",full:"Cost-to-Complete Forecast / Project Cost Forecast",definition:"A comprehensive monthly update of the project's cost status, combining actual costs, committed costs, pending changes, and CTC into a complete EAC for each cost code and the total project. The cost forecast is the primary monthly financial management report for the PM, owner, and lender.",example:"The Month 8 cost forecast showed: $12.4M actuals + $6.8M CTC + $1.1M pending COs = $20.3M EAC vs. $19.8M approved budget — a $500K adverse forecast triggering an owner review meeting."}],quiz:[{q:"EAC is calculated as:",opts:["Budget − Actual Costs","Actual Costs to Date + Cost-to-Complete","Original Budget + Change Orders","CTC only"],a:1,exp:"EAC = Actual Costs + CTC. This gives the total forecasted project cost at completion, which is compared to budget to determine variance."},{q:"The budget for electrical work is $1.8M. Actuals to date = $1.1M. CTC estimated by the PM = $850,000. What is the EAC and budget variance?",opts:["EAC $1.95M; −$150K over budget","EAC $1.95M; +$150K under budget","EAC $1.1M; on budget","EAC $2.1M; −$300K over budget"],a:0,exp:"EAC = $1.1M + $0.85M = $1.95M. Budget variance = $1.8M − $1.95M = −$150K (over budget)."},{q:'What is the difference between "actual cost" and "committed cost"?',opts:["They are identical","Actual cost = money already paid/invoiced; committed cost = total obligated (including contract values not yet invoiced) — committed cost is higher and better reflects total exposure","Committed cost excludes change orders","Actual cost includes CTC"],a:1,exp:"Actuals are money paid. Committed cost includes the full awarded subcontract/PO value — money obligated but not yet invoiced. Committed cost is the more conservative, complete picture of project exposure."},{q:"A budget variance of −$200,000 means:",opts:["The project is $200K under budget","The project is $200K over budget (EAC exceeds budget)","The change order value is $200K","The retainage amount is $200K"],a:1,exp:"Negative budget variance = over budget. Budget − EAC = −$200K means EAC > Budget by $200,000 — the project is forecasted to overrun."},{q:"Why is CTC more important than actual costs in project forecasting?",opts:["CTC is not important — only actuals matter","CTC is forward-looking; the money already spent can't be changed. CTC determines whether the project will finish on budget — actionable for cost recovery","CTC equals actual costs","Only the owner cares about CTC"],a:1,exp:"Past costs are fixed; CTC is what the PM can influence. An accurate CTC enables early identification of overruns while there's still time to take corrective action — VE, re-bid subcontracts, scope reduction."},{q:'What triggers a "corrective action plan" in project cost management?',opts:["When a project hits 50% complete","When the EAC exceeds the budget by a defined threshold (e.g., 2–5%), indicating the project needs active intervention to recover","When the first CO is approved","When retainage reaches 10%"],a:1,exp:"Most GCs and owners have thresholds (e.g., EAC > 3% over budget) that trigger a formal corrective action plan: identifying root causes, recovery measures (VE, productivity improvement), and accountability."},{q:"A project's Month 6 cost report shows: Actuals $8.5M, Committed $14.2M, Budget $20M. CTC = $6.2M. What is EAC?",opts:["$14.7M","$20.4M","$22.2M","$14.2M"],a:0,exp:"EAC = Actuals + CTC = $8.5M + $6.2M = $14.7M. (Committed cost is a different metric — it doesn't add CTC.)"},{q:"Cash flow projection is important for the GC because:",opts:["It determines contract price","It shows when the project will be cash-negative (paying subs/suppliers before receiving owner payment), informing working capital needs and billing strategy","It replaces cost forecasting","It determines retainage amounts"],a:1,exp:"Construction projects are typically cash-negative: the GC pays subs and materials before receiving owner payment. Cash flow projection identifies when working capital needs are highest, preventing liquidity surprises."},{q:'What is a "job cost report"?',opts:["A description of work completed","A financial report by cost code showing budget, actual costs, committed costs, EAC, and variance for each element of the project","A bid estimate","A change order log"],a:1,exp:"The job cost report is the PM's primary financial dashboard: budget vs. actual vs. committed vs. EAC for every cost code, enabling instant identification of over/under budget areas."},{q:"Concrete cost code shows budget $3.0M, actuals $2.4M, CTC $900K. What is the EAC and variance?",opts:["EAC $3.3M; −$300K over","EAC $2.4M; on budget","EAC $3.3M; +$300K under","EAC $900K; −$2.1M"],a:0,exp:"EAC = $2.4M + $0.9M = $3.3M. Variance = $3.0M − $3.3M = −$300K (over budget)."},{q:"Why should pending change orders be reflected in the cost forecast?",opts:["Pending COs don't affect the forecast until signed","Pending COs represent likely cost increases — including them in the forecast gives a complete and conservative picture of total project exposure","Pending COs reduce the budget","Only owner-approved COs matter"],a:1,exp:'A cost forecast that excludes pending COs understates project exposure. Including pending COs as "probable cost" provides a more accurate picture of total forecast, even before formal approval.'},{q:"When presenting an over-budget cost forecast to the owner, the PM should:",opts:["Minimize the bad news","Present the variance clearly, explain the causes, propose specific corrective actions with amounts and likelihood, and request owner decision on recovery options","Wait until the next month to report","Ask for a budget increase immediately"],a:1,exp:"Transparency is essential — the owner deserves timely, accurate information. The PM's credibility depends on clear variance reporting with causes and corrective actions, not minimizing or delaying bad news."},{q:'What does a "negative cash flow" period mean for a GC?',opts:["The project is losing money","During this period, the GC pays out more (to subs/suppliers) than it receives (from owner billing) — the GC's working capital decreases, requiring a credit line or reserves","The owner owes refund to GC","The project should stop"],a:1,exp:"Cash-negative periods are normal in construction: mobilization costs, material purchases, and sub payments often precede billings. The GC must have sufficient working capital or credit lines to bridge these periods."},{q:"A cost code is 80% complete but has used 95% of its budget. What does the cost forecast likely show?",opts:["The code will finish on budget","The code is trending over budget — if the remaining 20% of work costs even a fraction of the average rate, the budget will be exceeded","The code is under budget","No information can be drawn from this data"],a:1,exp:"95% of budget spent at 80% complete implies a significantly higher EAC. If costs track the same rate: budget needed for 100% = budget/0.80 = 118.75% of original — 18.75% over budget."},{q:"Why is the cost-to-complete (CTC) estimate the PM's most important monthly task?",opts:["Because it determines the pay app amount","Because it drives the EAC — an inaccurate CTC produces a misleading forecast, preventing early intervention while there's still time to recover","CTC is not important — lenders only care about actuals","Because it sets retainage amounts"],a:1,exp:"The CTC is the PM's forward-looking judgment about remaining cost. An overoptimistic CTC produces false comfort; an accurate CTC enables timely corrective action."},{q:"What is the benefit of tracking budget variance by individual cost code vs. only at the project total level?",opts:["Code-level tracking takes too long","Code-level analysis identifies which specific scopes are trending over or under, enabling targeted corrective action rather than just knowing the total variance","Only the total project variance matters","Individual variance tracking is only for large projects"],a:1,exp:"Code-level variance analysis is diagnostic: it tells you WHERE the overrun is (e.g., concrete cost code) rather than just the total number, enabling specific corrective action on the right scope."},{q:"The GC submits a monthly pay application based on percentage complete. If actual costs are higher than billed, what is the risk?",opts:["No risk — overbilling is common","Cash flow risk: the GC has paid out more than it has received, creating a working capital deficit","The owner pays the difference automatically","This only affects retainage"],a:1,exp:"Under-billing (actual costs > billings) is a cash flow problem: the GC is financing project costs out of its own working capital. The PM should ensure billing reflects actual earned value to avoid cash flow strain."},{q:"A project has $4M in pending COs not yet approved. The current budget is $18M. The cost forecast should show:",opts:["EAC based on $18M only","EAC = current budget analysis + pending COs (probability-weighted) as a probable cost — showing the full exposure picture of $18M+ up to $22M depending on CO approval","Just the $4M pending CO amount","$4M automatically added to the budget"],a:1,exp:"A complete cost forecast probability-weights pending COs and shows the full exposure range. This allows the owner and lender to understand the worst-case budget scenario before formal CO approval."},{q:"What corrective actions can a GC take when the cost forecast shows a 5% overrun?",opts:["Request an immediate budget increase from the owner","Identify VE opportunities in remaining scopes, re-bid subcontracts where possible, improve productivity, reduce GC overhead, negotiate with pending sub change orders","Issue a notice of claim to the owner","Reduce project scope unilaterally"],a:1,exp:"Common recovery strategies: VE on remaining scope, re-bid subcontracts, improve labor productivity, reduce GC general conditions, negotiate sub COs down, and pursue owner COs for any owner-caused overruns."}]},10:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Sep 8",title:"Session 1 — Superintendent Role & Daily Field Operations"},{day:"Wed Sep 10",title:"Session 2 — Substantial Completion vs Final Completion & Punch Lists"},{day:"Thu Sep 11",title:"Session 3 — Notice of Completion & Retainage Release in California"},{day:"Fri Sep 12",title:"Session 4 — Closeout Checklist Workshop: 30-Day Project Closeout Plan"}],vocabulary:[{term:"SUPERINTENDENT",full:"General Contractor Superintendent",definition:"The GC's on-site field manager responsible for daily project execution: directing subcontractors, managing schedule, enforcing safety, coordinating inspections, and maintaining project documentation. The superintendent is the GC's most critical field asset — their competence directly determines project success or failure.",example:"The senior superintendent managed 24 active subcontractors simultaneously during the peak construction phase, maintaining a 3-week look-ahead schedule and conducting daily 7 AM coordination meetings with all trade foremen."},{term:"DAILY REPORT",full:"Daily Construction Report",definition:"A written record prepared daily by the superintendent documenting: weather, workers on site (by trade), work performed, deliveries received, inspections, visitors, safety observations, and notable events. Daily reports are critical project records for delay claims, dispute resolution, and dispute prevention.",example:`The superintendent's July 15 daily report documented: "Owner's rep directed GC to remove and replace 200 LF of installed conduit per ASI #12 — work directed without formal CO. Logged as potential change order PCO #38."`},{term:"SWPPP",full:"Stormwater Pollution Prevention Plan",definition:"A state-required plan (CGP — Construction General Permit) for projects disturbing ≥1 acre that documents erosion and sediment control measures to prevent construction runoff from entering waterways. The superintendent must implement and maintain the SWPPP; violations carry significant fines from the Regional Water Quality Control Board.",example:"After a heavy rain event, the SWPPP's silt fence and fiber roll installations prevented sediment runoff from the 3.5-acre grading area; the superintendent documented compliance in the daily report and submitted the required rain event report."},{term:"SUBSTANTIAL COMPLETION",full:"Substantial Completion",definition:"The stage at which the project (or a specific portion) is sufficiently complete in accordance with the contract that the owner can use it for its intended purpose. The architect issues a Certificate of Substantial Completion. This is the milestone that: (1) starts the warranty period, (2) starts the punch list clock, (3) stops LD accrual, and (4) triggers the majority of retainage release.",example:"The architect issued the Certificate of Substantial Completion on November 15; the building was occupiable even though a punch list of 120 items remained; LD accrual stopped, the 1-year warranty period started, and $850,000 in retainage was released."},{term:"PUNCH LIST",full:"Punch List / Deficiency List",definition:"A list of items identified by the owner and/or architect during a pre-substantial completion walk that must be corrected or completed by the GC. Punch list items are minor in nature — substantial completion means the project is usable despite the punch list. All punch list items must be completed before final completion and final payment.",example:"The punch list walk-through generated 245 items; 90% were resolved within 30 days; the remaining 25 items (paint touch-ups, hardware adjustments, mechanical trim) were completed by the 45-day final completion deadline."},{term:"NOTICE OF COMPLETION",full:"Notice of Completion (NOC)",definition:"A California-specific document recorded with the county recorder after a project is completed, starting the shortened lien claim period for subcontractors and suppliers. The owner has 15 days to record the NOC; the GC has 15 days after owner recording. Recording triggers 30-day lien window for subs (vs. 90 days without NOC). Critical for retainage release.",example:"The owner recorded the NOC on November 20 (5 days after substantial completion); all 32 subcontractors were notified; their lien window ran until December 20, enabling the GC to release retainage after that date."}],quiz:[{q:"What is the primary role of the GC superintendent on a construction project?",opts:["Bid management","Daily on-site management: directing subs, managing schedule, enforcing safety, coordinating inspections, and maintaining field documentation","Design coordination","Contract negotiation"],a:1,exp:"The superintendent is the GC's field general — responsible for everything that happens on the job site every day. Their competence directly determines schedule, quality, and safety outcomes."},{q:"Why are daily construction reports critically important for the GC?",opts:["They are required by CEQA","They are contemporaneous records of events — essential for delay claims, change order documentation, and dispute resolution; a project without daily reports has no evidentiary foundation","They replace RFIs","They satisfy insurance requirements"],a:1,exp:"Daily reports are the GC's primary contemporaneous records. In a dispute, a well-maintained daily report is often the most persuasive evidence — it documents what happened the day it happened."},{q:"What is the significance of the Certificate of Substantial Completion?",opts:["It is the same as final completion","It marks when the project is usable for its intended purpose, starts the warranty period, stops LD accrual, starts the punch list period, and triggers retainage release","It is issued by the building department","It requires 100% punch list completion"],a:1,exp:"Substantial completion is the most important project milestone for both parties: owner can occupy/use the space; GC's LD exposure ends; warranty starts; retainage is substantially released."},{q:"The difference between substantial completion and final completion is:",opts:["They are identical","Substantial completion = project usable but punch list items remain; final completion = all punch list items resolved and all contract requirements fulfilled — triggers final payment","Final completion is issued by the building department","Substantial completion is not a legal concept"],a:1,exp:"Substantial completion: building is ready for use with minor deficiencies remaining. Final completion: every punch list item is done, all documentation is submitted, and the GC has met all contractual requirements for final payment."},{q:"In California, when must a property owner record a Notice of Completion?",opts:["30 days after project start","Within 15 days of project completion (or occupancy)","At the time of the building permit","Only when the lender requires it"],a:1,exp:"California Civil Code §8182 gives the owner 15 days after completion to record the NOC. Recording starts the shortened 30-day lien window for subcontractors and suppliers."},{q:"SWPPP compliance is the superintendent's responsibility because:",opts:["The architect prepares the SWPPP","The superintendent controls field operations and must implement, inspect, and maintain erosion controls daily — violations carry RWQCB fines and stop-work orders","Only public projects require SWPPP","The owner is responsible for SWPPP"],a:1,exp:'The SWPPP requires daily site inspections by a designated "Qualified SWPPP Practitioner." The superintendent ensures BMPs (silt fences, fiber rolls, wash-outs) are maintained, especially before and after rain events.'},{q:'What is a "rain event report" in the context of SWPPP?',opts:["A weather forecast","A required report documenting SWPPP BMP conditions before and after rain events, confirming erosion controls were in place and effective","A notice to the owner of rain delays","A lender requirement only"],a:1,exp:`California's Construction General Permit (CGP) requires "rain event action plans" and post-rain inspection reports documenting BMP performance — filed electronically through SMARTS.`},{q:"A punch list item involves a $5,000 cabinet repair. Should this prevent substantial completion?",opts:["Yes — the project is not complete until all punch list items are done","No — substantial completion means the project is usable for its intended purpose; minor deficiencies like a cabinet repair don't prevent substantial completion","Only if the owner objects","Depends on the contract"],a:1,exp:"Punch list items are inherently minor in nature. A $5,000 cabinet repair doesn't prevent the building from being used for its intended purpose — the project qualifies for substantial completion despite this minor deficiency."},{q:"After the NOC is recorded, subcontractors have how long to file a mechanics lien in California?",opts:["90 days from recording","30 days from NOC recording","60 days","6 months"],a:1,exp:"California Civil Code §8412: after owner records a NOC, subs/suppliers have 30 days to record a mechanics lien. Without a NOC, they have 90 days from completion."},{q:"A superintendent discovers a significant construction defect during the project. What should their first action be?",opts:["Fix it quietly and don't tell anyone","Document it in the daily report, notify the PM immediately, and determine the cause and responsible party before proceeding with repair","Issue a stop-work notice immediately","Contact the owner's attorney"],a:1,exp:"Discovery of a defect requires immediate documentation and escalation. The daily report creates a contemporaneous record; the PM must assess cause (design vs. construction), repair cost, and owner notification requirements."},{q:"Why should the superintendent conduct a pre-inspection walk with subs before the formal punch list walk?",opts:["To avoid the formal inspection","To catch and resolve obvious deficiencies before the owner/architect inspection, reducing the formal punch list count and demonstrating quality consciousness","Required by SWPPP","To confirm as-built drawings"],a:1,exp:"Self-inspection walks allow the GC to clean up obvious issues (paint touch-ups, hardware adjustments, cleaning) before the formal punch list walk. Fewer formal punch list items = faster closeout and better owner impression."},{q:"Retainage on a GC's subcontracts is typically released when:",opts:["The GC receives its own final payment","At substantial completion of the sub's scope, the GC releases sub retainage (sometimes held until final lien period expiration for safety)","After 6 months regardless of project status","Only when the owner releases GC retainage"],a:1,exp:"California law and good practice call for releasing sub retainage at substantial completion of their scope (not tied to overall project completion). Withholding retainage indefinitely is inequitable and creates lien risk."},{q:"What daily data is most important in a construction daily report?",opts:["Weather only","Trade headcount by discipline, work performed, materials received, inspections, notable events, owner/architect visits, and any verbal directions received","Only safety incidents","Just the date and weather"],a:1,exp:"A complete daily report captures everything relevant to project status: who was there, what work happened, what arrived, what was inspected, who visited, and any unusual directions — the full picture of that day."},{q:"An owner occupies the building before formal substantial completion. What legal issues does this create?",opts:["No issues — occupancy is the owner's right","Owner's early occupancy can be deemed a de facto substantial completion: starting the warranty period, stopping LDs, and potentially releasing retainage early — the GC should get this formalized","The GC can demand immediate final payment","Only affects SWPPP requirements"],a:1,exp:"Early occupancy by the owner is often treated as acceptance/substantial completion, even without a formal certificate. GCs should formalize the substantial completion date when the owner takes possession to ensure warranty, LD, and retainage protections."},{q:"The GC's SWPPP requires inspection after every 0.5-inch rain event. Who is typically responsible for conducting this inspection?",opts:["The architect","A Qualified SWPPP Practitioner (QSP) — typically the superintendent or designated site staff with required certification","The county inspector","The civil engineer"],a:1,exp:"California CGP requires inspections by a Qualified SWPPP Practitioner (QSP). On most commercial projects, the GC designates a certified superintendent or site supervisor as the QSP."},{q:"What is the relationship between substantial completion and the project warranty period?",opts:["The warranty starts at final completion","The 1-year (or longer) warranty period starts at substantial completion — not at final payment or project start","Warranty starts when the last CO is signed","Warranty is triggered by first occupancy"],a:1,exp:"Per AIA A201 §12.2.2, the warranty period begins at substantial completion. The GC is responsible for correcting warranty defects discovered within the warranty period after that date."},{q:"A punch list has 85 items. 60 were resolved in week 1; 20 more in week 2. 5 remain at the contract final completion deadline. What is the consequence?",opts:["No consequence — 5 items is minimal","The GC has not achieved final completion per the contract; the owner can withhold final payment and potentially back-charge the cost of resolving the remaining items","The owner must accept completion","Only retainage is affected"],a:1,exp:"Final completion requires all punch list items resolved. With 5 items outstanding at the deadline, the GC is technically in breach — the owner can withhold final payment and, if unresolved, hire others to complete and back-charge the GC."},{q:'Daily reports documenting "crew working without verbal direction from owner rep to proceed" protect the GC by:',opts:["Proving the GC was on site","Establishing that no owner-directed change order was verbally issued — protective when an owner later claims the GC added scope without authorization","Satisfying SWPPP requirements","Reducing lien claims"],a:0,exp:'Actually, the valuable documentation is recording when an owner rep DOES give verbal directions. Daily reports that capture "owner rep directed..." protect the GC in constructive change claims.'},{q:"What documentation package should accompany the final payment application?",opts:["Only the final invoice","Final lien releases from all subs and suppliers, as-built drawings, O&M manuals, equipment warranties, completed punch list sign-off, and final permit sign-off","Just the retainage release form","SWPPP final report only"],a:1,exp:"Final payment requires comprehensive contract closeout documentation: lien releases protect the owner from sub liens; as-builts, O&Ms, and warranties are contractual deliverables the owner needs for building operations."}]},11:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Sep 15",title:"Session 1 — Monthly Owner Report Structure & Key Content"},{day:"Wed Sep 17",title:"Session 2 — Earned Value Analysis: SPI & CPI Calculation"},{day:"Thu Sep 18",title:"Session 3 — Risk Log & Owner Decision Items"},{day:"Fri Sep 19",title:"Session 4 — Reporting Workshop: Prepare Month 6 Owner Report"}],vocabulary:[{term:"MONTHLY OWNER REPORT",full:"Monthly Construction Progress Report",definition:"A comprehensive monthly report to the owner summarizing project status across cost, schedule, safety, quality, and key risks/decisions. The monthly owner report is the GC's primary accountability document — it demonstrates transparency, professionalism, and proactive management. Most GMP contracts require it.",example:"The Month 9 owner report included: executive summary (on schedule, 1.5% over budget), cost forecast, updated schedule, 12 photos, safety statistics (0 recordables), 5 open RFIs summary, 3 pending COs, 2 owner decisions required, and a risk log update."},{term:"PERCENT COMPLETE",full:"Percent Complete",definition:"An estimate of how much of the project (or a specific scope element) has been completed. Used in cost reporting to calculate earned value and in schedule reporting to show progress. Percent complete can be measured by units installed, cost incurred, or engineering judgment — consistency in method is important.",example:"The concrete cost code was 78% complete (assessed by installed CY vs. total CY from QTO); the MEP was 45% complete based on rough-in inspections passed vs. total required inspections."},{term:"EARNED VALUE",full:"Earned Value (EV)",definition:"The budgeted cost of work performed — the budget value of completed work. EV = Budget × % Complete. Earned value enables objective measurement of project progress independent of cost incurred. It is the basis for SPI and CPI calculations and provides a performance baseline for schedule and cost health.",example:"Project budget: $20M. Percent complete: 35%. Earned Value (EV) = $20M × 35% = $7.0M. Planned Value (PV) was $7.5M, indicating the project is behind planned progress."},{term:"SCHEDULE PERFORMANCE INDEX",full:"Schedule Performance Index (SPI)",definition:"A ratio measuring schedule efficiency: SPI = Earned Value (EV) ÷ Planned Value (PV). SPI > 1.0 = ahead of schedule; SPI < 1.0 = behind schedule; SPI = 1.0 = on schedule. SPI helps quantify schedule health independent of cost.",example:"EV = $7.0M; PV = $7.5M; SPI = 7.0 ÷ 7.5 = 0.933 — the project is 6.7% behind planned schedule progress."},{term:"COST PERFORMANCE INDEX",full:"Cost Performance Index (CPI)",definition:"A ratio measuring cost efficiency: CPI = Earned Value (EV) ÷ Actual Cost (AC). CPI > 1.0 = under budget (getting more value per dollar spent); CPI < 1.0 = over budget; CPI = 1.0 = exactly on budget. CPI is the primary indicator of cost health at a point in time.",example:"EV = $7.0M; AC = $7.8M; CPI = 7.0 ÷ 7.8 = 0.897 — the project is getting only $0.90 of value for every $1.00 spent, indicating a 10.3% cost overrun trend."},{term:"RISK LOG",full:"Project Risk Log / Risk Register",definition:"A living register of known project risks, updated monthly in the owner report. Each risk entry includes: description, probability, impact, mitigation strategy, owner, and status. The risk log enables proactive management — identifying risks before they become issues and communicating risk status to the owner.",example:'The Month 7 risk log had 8 active risks; the top risk was "long-lead switchgear: 6-week delivery window at risk due to manufacturer backlog — probability HIGH, impact 3 weeks to critical path. Mitigation: expediter assigned, alternate manufacturer identified."'}],quiz:[{q:"SPI is calculated as:",opts:["Actual Cost ÷ Planned Value","Earned Value ÷ Planned Value","Budget ÷ Actual Cost","Earned Value ÷ Budget"],a:1,exp:"SPI = EV ÷ PV. > 1.0 = ahead of schedule; < 1.0 = behind schedule. It measures schedule efficiency: how much planned value has actually been earned vs. what was planned to be complete by now."},{q:"CPI is calculated as:",opts:["Earned Value ÷ Actual Cost","Actual Cost ÷ Earned Value","Budget ÷ Earned Value","Planned Value ÷ Earned Value"],a:0,exp:"CPI = EV ÷ AC. > 1.0 = under budget (efficient); < 1.0 = over budget; = 1.0 = on budget. It measures cost efficiency: how much earned value is received per dollar of actual cost."},{q:"Project: Budget $15M, % complete 40%, Actual costs $7.2M. Calculate EV, SPI (PV=$6.5M), and CPI.",opts:["EV=$6M, SPI=0.923, CPI=0.833","EV=$6M, SPI=1.077, CPI=1.2","EV=$7.2M, SPI=1.0, CPI=1.0","EV=$6M, SPI=0.923, CPI=0.923"],a:0,exp:"EV = $15M × 40% = $6M. SPI = $6M ÷ $6.5M (PV) = 0.923. CPI = $6M ÷ $7.2M (AC) = 0.833. Both SPI and CPI < 1.0: project is behind schedule AND over budget."},{q:"What does an SPI of 0.85 mean in plain language?",opts:["Project is 15% over budget","Project has only completed 85% of the scheduled work — 15% behind plan","Project is 15% ahead of schedule","No meaningful interpretation without more data"],a:1,exp:"SPI = 0.85 means the project has accomplished 85% of what was planned to be complete by now — the project is 15% behind the planned schedule."},{q:"What should a monthly owner report include at minimum?",opts:["Only the budget update","Executive summary, cost status (EAC vs. budget), schedule status (SPI), photos, safety statistics, key RFI/submittal status, pending COs, owner decision items, and risk log","Just the schedule update","Only safety and quality"],a:1,exp:"A comprehensive monthly report covers all dimensions of project health: cost, schedule, safety, quality, information management, pending changes, owner decisions, and risks. This is the owner's primary project visibility document."},{q:'What is the "owner decision items" section of a monthly report?',opts:["Items the owner must do","A list of pending decisions that require the owner's input, authorization, or action — with required response dates to prevent schedule impact","Questions from the design team","Change orders awaiting signature only"],a:1,exp:"Owner decision items are the GC's proactive communication to the owner about pending decisions (material selections, CO approvals, design direction) that, if delayed, will impact schedule or cost — keeping the owner accountable."},{q:"A CPI of 1.15 indicates:",opts:["Project is 15% over budget","Project is 15% under budget — getting $1.15 of earned value for every $1.00 spent","No cost variance","The schedule is 15% ahead"],a:1,exp:"CPI > 1.0 means the project is cost-efficient — earning more value per dollar spent than budgeted. CPI = 1.15 means for every $1 spent, $1.15 of budget value is being accomplished."},{q:"An SPI < 1.0 and CPI < 1.0 simultaneously indicates:",opts:["Project is ahead of schedule and under budget","Project is behind schedule AND over budget — the worst combined performance scenario","Project is on schedule but over budget","SPI and CPI don't interact"],a:1,exp:"Both metrics < 1.0 is the worst situation: behind schedule (SPI < 1) AND spending more than earned value (CPI < 1). This typically requires a formal recovery plan."},{q:`The risk log entry for a long-lead switchgear shows "Probability: HIGH, Impact: 3 weeks to critical path." What is the PM's appropriate action?`,opts:["No action — risks are tracked not addressed","Activate mitigation: expedite the order, identify alternate suppliers, pre-order critical components, and update the owner in the monthly report with mitigation status","Delete the risk once identified","Request a budget increase"],a:1,exp:"A HIGH-probability, high-impact risk requires active mitigation. The PM must take specific action (expedite, alternate supplier) and keep the owner informed — waiting passively is not a risk management strategy."},{q:'What is the difference between a "risk" and an "issue" in project management?',opts:["They are identical","A risk is a potential future event that could impact the project (uncertain); an issue is a risk that has materialized and is now actively impacting the project","Issues are only safety-related","Risks are only financial"],a:1,exp:"Risks are forward-looking probabilities (may occur). Issues are current problems (have occurred). The risk log tracks risks; a separate issues log tracks active problems requiring resolution."},{q:"Monthly owner reports are important for the GC's business relationship because:",opts:["They are required by lenders only","Consistent, transparent reporting builds owner trust, demonstrates professional management, reduces disputes by creating a shared understanding of project status, and protects the GC's reputation","They reduce insurance requirements","They replace the need for RFIs"],a:1,exp:"Proactive, accurate monthly reporting is a competitive differentiator for GCs. Owners remember which GCs kept them informed and which surprised them at the end — transparency builds repeat business."},{q:"EV = $8.5M, AC = $9.2M, PV = $9.0M. Calculate SPI and CPI.",opts:["SPI=0.944, CPI=0.924","SPI=0.924, CPI=0.944","SPI=0.944, CPI=1.082","SPI=1.0, CPI=0.924"],a:0,exp:"SPI = EV ÷ PV = $8.5M ÷ $9.0M = 0.944. CPI = EV ÷ AC = $8.5M ÷ $9.2M = 0.924. Both metrics < 1.0: behind schedule and over budget."},{q:'What is the primary benefit of earned value analysis over simple "budget vs. actuals" comparison?',opts:["EV is simpler to calculate","EV integrates schedule and cost: it measures whether work is being accomplished at the budgeted efficiency, not just whether money is being spent","EV replaces the need for schedule updates","Only lenders use EV analysis"],a:1,exp:"Budget vs. actuals only shows spending rate. EV analysis shows whether work value is being produced at that spend rate — a project can be under budget because it's behind schedule, not because it's efficient."},{q:"The monthly report photos should show:",opts:["Only completed work","Current site conditions, progress on key activities, notable conditions (weather, safety), and documentation of owner-directed changes or unusual conditions","Only problem areas","Whatever looks good for marketing"],a:1,exp:"Photos are the most powerful part of the monthly report. They should show real project status: progress, conditions, notable events — and document owner-directed activities, site conditions, and quality."},{q:"A project has SPI = 1.10 but CPI = 0.88. What does this indicate?",opts:["Project is doing well on all measures","Project is ahead of schedule but over budget — accelerating production is costing more than budgeted","Project is behind schedule and under budget","Both metrics show the same thing"],a:1,exp:"SPI > 1 = ahead of schedule; CPI < 1 = over budget. The project is progressing fast but not efficiently — the acceleration may be costing premium rates, overtime, or quality rework."},{q:"The owner wants a dashboard-style one-page executive summary. What key metrics should appear?",opts:["Only RFI count","Schedule status (SPI), cost status (CPI + EAC vs. budget), safety (recordable rate), key milestone status, and top 3 risks — all with traffic light indicators","Full cost report","Subcontractor headcount only"],a:1,exp:"An effective executive dashboard uses traffic lights (green/yellow/red) for schedule, cost, safety, and milestones — giving the owner instant visual status before reading any detail."},{q:"What is the purpose of tracking the count of open vs. closed RFIs and submittals in the monthly report?",opts:["To count paperwork only","To show information management health — a growing backlog of open items signals potential coordination problems that may impact schedule","Required by CEQA","Lender requirement only"],a:1,exp:"RFI/submittal metrics track information flow efficiency. A growing backlog of open items signals design team responsiveness problems or contractor submission delays — both of which can cascade to schedule impacts."},{q:"When presenting a budget overrun in the monthly report, the GC should:",opts:["Hide the overrun until it's certain",'Report the variance clearly, explain specific causes (e.g., "concrete division tracking $200K over due to DSC claim"), describe recovery actions being taken, and request owner input if needed',"Blame subcontractors in the report","Wait for the lender to ask"],a:1,exp:"Transparency in reporting cost variances — with causes and recovery actions — is the professional standard. Owners are partners in cost management; early, honest reporting enables joint recovery planning."}]},12:{sessions:[{day:"Mon Sep 22",title:"Session 1 — Bid Package Structure: Scope Narrative, Documents & Process"},{day:"Wed Sep 24",title:"Session 2 — Subcontractor Prequalification & Bid Bond Requirements"},{day:"Thu Sep 25",title:"Session 3 — Procurement Schedule & Award Process"},{day:"Fri Sep 26",title:"Session 4 — Domain 2 Capstone: Full Bid Package Presentation"}],vocabulary:[{term:"BID PACKAGE",full:"Subcontractor Bid Package",definition:"A complete set of documents issued to bidding subcontractors to solicit competitive pricing for a specific scope of work. A bid package includes: invitation to bid, scope narrative, relevant drawings/specs (CSI sections), bid form, schedule requirements, insurance requirements, and subcontract terms. Complete bid packages reduce scope gaps and improve bid quality.",example:"The mechanical bid package included: scope narrative (14 pages), M-sheets 1-22, Div 22/23 specs, alternates list, project schedule, insurance requirements, draft AIA A401 subcontract, and bid form — issued to 5 qualified mechanical subs."},{term:"PROCUREMENT SCHEDULE",full:"Procurement Schedule / Long-Lead Schedule",definition:"A schedule tracking the procurement timeline for key materials and equipment: bid date, award date, submittal due date, approval date, fabrication time, and delivery date. The procurement schedule integrates with the CPM to ensure long-lead items are ordered in time for construction. Critical long-lead items (switchgear, elevators, curtain wall) are often 16–52 weeks.",example:"The procurement schedule showed that main electrical switchgear required a 32-week lead time; to meet the Month 8 electrical rough-in, the switchgear had to be ordered by Month 3 — driven by the procurement schedule, not the construction CPM."},{term:"SUBCONTRACTOR PREQUALIFICATION",full:"Subcontractor Prequalification",definition:"The process of evaluating subcontractors before inviting them to bid, assessing: financial strength, bonding capacity, safety record (EMR), relevant experience, staff capacity, and references. Prequalification reduces the risk of awarding to a subcontractor that cannot financially or operationally deliver the project.",example:"Before the $4M MEP package, the GC prequalified 8 mechanical subs; 2 failed financial review, 1 had an unacceptable EMR of 1.6; 5 qualified subs were invited to bid, reducing the risk of a performance default."},{term:"BID BOND",full:"Bid Bond",definition:"A surety bond submitted with a bid guaranteeing that if the bidder is awarded the contract, it will execute the contract and provide required performance/payment bonds. If the bidder fails to execute, the bid bond pays the owner the difference between the winning bid and the next-lowest bid (up to the bond penalty). Bid bonds are typically 5–10% of the bid amount.",example:"The bid bond was 5% of the $3.8M bid = $190,000; when the apparent low bidder was unable to obtain a performance bond post-award, the owner claimed the bid bond, recovering the $85,000 difference between the first and second bids."},{term:"CONTRACT AWARD",full:"Subcontract Award / Contract Award",definition:"The formal decision to select and execute a contract with a specific subcontractor or vendor. Award follows bid leveling, scope confirmation, and award recommendation. Award is formalized by the execution of the subcontract agreement. The award notice (letter of intent) may be issued before full subcontract execution to allow the sub to order materials.",example:"After leveling 4 bids for HVAC, the PM issued a Letter of Intent to the $2.8M leveled low bidder on March 15, authorizing the sub to order long-lead equipment while the subcontract was being finalized."},{term:"SCOPE NARRATIVE",full:"Bid Package Scope Narrative",definition:"A written description of exactly what scope is included in a bid package: work included, work excluded, interfaces with other trades, schedule requirements, and any special conditions. The scope narrative is the most important part of a bid package — it defines what the sub is pricing and prevents scope gaps.",example:`The plumbing scope narrative explicitly stated: "Includes all domestic water, sanitary, storm, and gas piping to 5' outside building. Excludes site utilities (by civil), fire sprinkler (by fire protection sub), and all HVAC plumbing connections (by mechanical sub)."`}],quiz:[{q:"What is the most important element of a subcontractor bid package?",opts:["The bid bond form","The scope narrative — clearly defining what is included, excluded, and at the interface with other trades","The insurance requirements","The payment terms"],a:1,exp:"The scope narrative is the foundation of the bid package. It defines exactly what the sub is pricing — without a clear scope narrative, every bid will be based on different assumptions, making leveling impossible."},{q:"Why is subcontractor prequalification important before bid invitation?",opts:["It reduces the number of bids","It ensures bidders have the financial strength, bonding capacity, safety record, and relevant experience to actually deliver the project — reducing default risk","It's required by California law on all projects","It eliminates the need for performance bonds"],a:1,exp:`Prequalification prevents awarding to a sub that "wins" on price but can't financially or operationally deliver the project — one of the most costly GC mistakes.`},{q:"A bid bond of 5% is required on a $5M subcontract. What is the bond amount?",opts:["$50,000","$100,000","$250,000","$500,000"],a:2,exp:"5% × $5,000,000 = $250,000 bid bond."},{q:'What is a "Letter of Intent" (LOI) in the award process?',opts:["The final subcontract","A written notice from the GC authorizing the sub to start work (typically ordering materials) before the full subcontract is executed","The prequalification document","The bid bond certificate"],a:1,exp:"An LOI bridges the gap between award decision and full subcontract execution. For long-lead equipment, the LOI allows the sub to order materials while contract documents are finalized — preventing schedule delays."},{q:"What information is in a procurement schedule that is NOT in the CPM construction schedule?",opts:["Activity durations","Submittal deadlines, approval dates, fabrication times, and delivery windows for equipment and materials — the procurement chain leading to delivery on site","Labor resource assignments","Weather allowances"],a:1,exp:"The procurement schedule tracks the entire supply chain from order to delivery. A CPM shows when materials are needed on site; the procurement schedule shows all the steps to get there."},{q:"Long-lead items (32-week switchgear, 52-week elevator) must be identified:",opts:["During final construction","At the start of preconstruction or early design — procurement schedules must be built backward from required on-site dates to determine when orders must be placed","At bid time only","After GMP is signed"],a:1,exp:"Long-lead procurement starts months before field installation. A 32-week switchgear must be ordered 32 weeks before the electrical rough-in — which might be well before the GMP is signed."},{q:"What is the difference between a bid bond and a performance bond?",opts:["They are identical","Bid bond guarantees the bidder will execute the contract and provide bonds at award; performance bond guarantees the subcontractor will complete their scope of work","Performance bond is submitted with the bid","Bid bonds are not refundable"],a:1,exp:"Bid bond protects the pre-award period (bidder won't walk away after winning). Performance bond protects the construction period (sub will actually complete their work). Two different risks, two different bonds."},{q:"An EMR (Experience Modification Rate) above what value is typically disqualifying in subcontractor prequalification?",opts:["0.5","1.0","1.2 or 1.5","2.0"],a:2,exp:"EMR measures a company's safety performance vs. industry average. Most GCs disqualify subs with EMR above 1.2–1.5 (20–50% above average). An EMR of 1.0 is exactly average; below 1.0 is better than average."},{q:"How does a tight bid spread (all bids within 5%) differ from a wide spread (ranging 30–40%) in terms of market signals?",opts:["A tight spread means bidders didn't read the documents carefully","A tight spread suggests all bidders priced the same scope consistently — good bid package quality; a wide spread often signals scope interpretation differences or significant risk pricing by some bidders","Wide spreads indicate fraud","They provide identical information"],a:1,exp:"Tight bids indicate consistent scope interpretation and competitive market. Wide bid spreads signal that bidders interpreted scope differently — usually requiring leveling to understand what each bidder actually priced."},{q:"A complete bid package for a large MEP scope would include:",opts:["Only the drawings","Invitation to bid, scope narrative, relevant M/E/P drawings and specifications, alternates, project schedule, insurance requirements, bond requirements, bid form, and draft subcontract terms","Only the bid form","Insurance requirements only"],a:1,exp:"A complete bid package gives the sub everything they need to provide a complete and competitive bid. Missing elements create scope ambiguity, late clarifications, and ultimately scope gaps in the awarded contract."},{q:"What is the purpose of a bid form in a bid package?",opts:["Sets the owner's budget","A standard format requiring each sub to provide pricing in a consistent structure (base bid, alternates, unit prices, exclusions) — enabling direct comparison during bid leveling","Substitutes for the scope narrative","Lists the sub's references"],a:1,exp:"A bid form standardizes the price submission format. When all subs use the same form, comparing base bids, alternates, and unit prices is straightforward — reducing leveling complexity."},{q:"Why should subcontract terms (insurance, payment, warranty) be part of the bid package?",opts:["To confuse bidders","So subs understand the full contractual obligations before pricing — allowing them to reflect bonding costs, insurance requirements, and cash flow needs in their bid","Only required on public projects","Terms are negotiated after award only"],a:1,exp:'Sharing subcontract terms before bid allows subs to price the full obligation: if the contract requires payment bonds, the sub can include bond cost. Surprises at award (like "now we need a bond") create disputes.'},{q:"A procurement schedule shows: Switchgear lead time = 28 weeks. Required on site = Week 36 of construction. When must the order be placed?",opts:["Week 36","Week 8 (Week 36 − 28 weeks = Week 8)","Week 28","Week 14"],a:1,exp:"Order must be placed at Week 36 − 28 weeks = Week 8. The procurement schedule reveals that the switchgear must be ordered 8 weeks into the construction period."},{q:'What is a "scope of exclusions" in a bid package?',opts:["Items the GC wants to delete from the project","A list of specifically excluded items in the scope narrative — work that is NOT part of the bid package even if shown on relevant drawings","Work the owner excludes from the contract","Optional alternates"],a:1,exp:`Explicit exclusions prevent scope confusion. A plumbing scope narrative might list: "Excludes fire sprinkler piping, HVAC connections, and site utilities" — ensuring those items don't create overlapping bids with other trades.`},{q:"After all bids are leveled and an award recommendation is made, what is the GC's next step?",opts:["Send the sub to work immediately","Obtain owner or project director approval of the award recommendation, then execute the subcontract agreement with the selected sub","Issue a bid bond only","File with the county recorder"],a:1,exp:"The award recommendation goes through the GC's internal approval process (PM → project director → owner if required by contract) before execution. The subcontract is then issued and signed by both parties."},{q:"The Domain 2 capstone bid package exercise requires demonstrating mastery of:",opts:["Only estimating fundamentals","All 12 weeks: delivery methods, drawings/specs, estimating, bid leveling, scheduling, RFIs, subcontracts, change orders, cost forecasting, field ops, owner reporting, and bid package assembly","Only subcontract management","Scheduling only"],a:1,exp:"The Domain 2 capstone integrates all 12 weeks: a complete subcontractor bid package demonstrates ability to prepare scope narratives, select bidders, levy bids, award, manage, and report — the full commercial construction PM lifecycle."},{q:"A subcontractor's prequalification shows EMR 0.78, bonding capacity $5M, and 6 comparable projects completed. This sub is:",opts:["Disqualified for low EMR","Highly qualified: EMR below 1.0 shows better-than-average safety; $5M bonding is adequate; relevant experience established","Requires more information before qualification","Only qualified for projects under $1M"],a:1,exp:"EMR 0.78 (below 1.0 = better than industry average safety), sufficient bonding capacity, and relevant experience are strong indicators of a qualified subcontractor — invite to bid."},{q:'Why does a GC issue a "no-bid list" for some subcontractors?',opts:["To reduce competition and keep prices high","To exclude subs who have demonstrated poor performance, safety violations, or financial issues on past projects — protecting the GC from known risks","Required by CEQA","To limit bidding to only union trades"],a:1,exp:'A no-bid list (sometimes called a "do-not-use" list) excludes subs with documented performance failures. Past performance on GC projects is the strongest predictor of future performance.'},{q:"The HTA Builder Academy Domain 2 trains practitioners to:",opts:["Design buildings","Manage commercial construction projects end-to-end: from delivery method selection through bid management, subcontract administration, cost forecasting, field operations, and owner reporting","Perform financial analysis only","Write specifications"],a:1,exp:"Domain 2 develops the complete commercial construction PM skill set: the knowledge to run a project from preconstruction through closeout, communicate with owners and subs, and manage cost, schedule, quality, and risk."}]}};export{e as D,t as a};
